7
00:00:21,940 --> 00:00:32,260
Not because my childhood was different from that of others, not because I have anything strange to relate, anything new to tell, are these words written.

8
00:00:32,260 --> 00:00:47,010
For the other reason rather that I was a child as other children, that my memories are their memories, as my hopes were their hopes, my dreams their dreams, my fears their fears.

9
00:00:47,010 --> 00:00:52,180
I open the book of memory to tear out some pages for you others.

10
00:00:52,180 --> 00:00:57,890
There is nothing here that is not in my most clear and vivid recollection.

11
00:00:57,890 --> 00:01:09,240
When I was a little child I used to pray fervently, tearfully, that when I should be grown up I might never forget what I thought and felt and suffered then.

12
00:01:09,240 --> 00:01:14,900
Let these pages speak for me, and bear witness that I have not forgotten.

13
00:01:16,840 --> 00:01:20,340
PART 1
STUART PLAID

14
00:01:21,540 --> 00:01:37,760
When I was small and teachable my mother was compelled to much travel and change of scene by the illness of my elder sister; and as she liked to have me more or less within reach, I changed schools as a place-hunter changes his politics.

15
00:01:37,760 --> 00:01:42,440
The first school I went to was a Mrs. Arthur's—at Brighton.

16
00:01:42,440 --> 00:01:52,240
I remember very little about the lessons, because I was only seven years old, but I remember—to my inmost fibre I remember the play.

17
00:01:52,240 --> 00:02:00,310
There was a yard behind the house—no garden and there I used to play with another small child whose name I have forgotten.

18
00:02:00,310 --> 00:02:06,640
But I know that she wore a Stuart plaid frock, and that I detested her.

19
00:02:07,820 --> 00:02:12,490
On the first day of my arrival we were sent into the "playground" with our toys.

20
00:02:12,490 --> 00:02:24,050
Stuart plaid, as I must call her, having no other name, had a battered doll and three scallop-shells I had a very complete little set of pewter tea-things in a cardboard box.

21
00:02:24,050 --> 00:02:27,780
"Let's change for a bit," said Stuart plaid.

22
00:02:27,780 --> 00:02:32,530
Mingled politeness and shyness compelled my acquiescence.

23
00:02:32,530 --> 00:02:37,840
She took my new tea-things, and I disconsolately nursed the battered torso of her doll.

24
00:02:37,840 --> 00:02:46,080
But this grew very wearisome, and I, feeling satisfied that the claims of courtesy had been fully met, protested mildly.

25
00:02:46,080 --> 00:02:55,890
"Now then," said Stuart plaid, looking up from the tea-things, "don't be so selfish; besides, they're horrid little stupid tin things.

26
00:02:55,890 --> 00:02:58,130
I wouldn't give twopence for them."

27
00:02:58,130 --> 00:03:02,340
"But I don't want you to give twopence for them; I want them back."

28
00:03:02,340 --> 00:03:04,040
"Oh, no you don't!"

29
00:03:04,040 --> 00:03:11,670
"Yes I do," said I, roused by her depreciation of my property—, "and I'll have them too, so there!"

30
00:03:11,670 --> 00:03:18,340
I advanced towards her—I am afraid with some half-formed determination of pulling her hair.

31
00:03:18,340 --> 00:03:23,440
"All right," she said, "you stand there and I'll put them in the box and give them to you."

32
00:03:23,440 --> 00:03:25,160
"Promise!"

33
00:03:25,160 --> 00:03:27,980
"Yes, if you don't move."

34
00:03:27,980 --> 00:03:30,260
She turned her back on me.

35
00:03:30,260 --> 00:03:33,810
It took her a very long time to put them in the box.

36
00:03:33,810 --> 00:03:38,970
I stood tingling with indignation, and a growing desire to slap her face.

37
00:03:38,970 --> 00:03:41,150
Presently she turned.

38
00:03:41,150 --> 00:03:47,440
"You would have them back," she said, grinning unpleasantly, "and here they are."

39
00:03:47,440 --> 00:03:50,060
She put them into my hands.

40
00:03:50,060 --> 00:03:56,560
She had bitten every single cup, saucer, and plate into a formless lump!

41
00:03:57,640 --> 00:04:04,040
While I stood speechless with anger and misery, she came close to me and said tauntingly:

42
00:04:04,040 --> 00:04:05,020
"There, now!

43
00:04:05,020 --> 00:04:07,620
aren't you sorry you didn't let me have them?"

44
00:04:07,620 --> 00:04:12,750
"I'll go home," I said, struggling between pride and tears.

45
00:04:12,750 --> 00:04:23,120
"Oh, no you won't," said Stuart plaid, thrusting her mocking face close to mine; "and if you say a word about it I'll say you did it and pinched me as well.

46
00:04:23,120 --> 00:04:26,920
And Mrs. Arthur'll believe me, because I'm not a new girl, and you are!"

47
00:04:26,920 --> 00:04:32,920
I turned away without a word, and I never did tell—till now.

48
00:04:32,920 --> 00:04:37,460
But I never said another word to Stuart plaid out of school.

49
00:04:37,460 --> 00:04:40,500
She tortured me unremittingly.

50
00:04:40,500 --> 00:04:52,690
When I had been at school a week or two my paint-box suffered at her hands, but I bore it meekly and in silence, only seeking to replace my Vandyke brown by mud from the garden.

51
00:04:52,690 --> 00:05:00,820
Chinese white I sought to manufacture by a mixture of chalk picked up on the sea-shore, and milk from my mug at tea-time.

52
00:05:00,820 --> 00:05:03,460
It was never a successful industry.

53
00:05:03,460 --> 00:05:23,750
I remember the hot white streets, and the flies, and Brill's baths, and the Western Road, and the bitter pang of passing, at the end of a long procession, our own house, where always some one might be at the window, and never any one was.

54
00:05:23,750 --> 00:05:36,950
I used to go home on Saturdays, and then all bitterness was so swallowed up in the bliss of the homereturning, that I actually forgot the miseries of my school-life; but I was very unhappy there.

55
00:05:36,950 --> 00:05:44,140
Mrs. Arthur and the big girls were kind enough to me, but Stuart plaid was enough to blight any lot.

56
00:05:44,140 --> 00:05:59,620
She blighted mine, and I suppose no prisoner ever hailed the falling of his fetters with the joy I felt when at last, after three or four days of headache and tears, I was wrapped in a blanket and taken home with the measles.

57
00:06:01,280 --> 00:06:07,470
When I got better we went for the midsummer holidays to a lovely cottage among the beech-woods of Buckinghamshire.

58
00:06:07,470 --> 00:06:20,640
I shall never forget the sense of rest and delight that filled my small heart when I slipped out under the rustic porch at five o'clock the first morning, and felt the cool velvet turf under my feet.

59
00:06:20,640 --> 00:06:24,330
Brighton pavement had been so hard and hot.

60
00:06:24,330 --> 00:06:36,760
Then, instead of the long rows of dazzling houses with their bow windows and green-painted balconies, there were lovely trees acacias and elms, and a big copper beech.

61
00:06:36,760 --> 00:06:43,240
In the school walks we never had found any flowers but little pink bind-weed, by the dusty roadside.

62
00:06:43,240 --> 00:06:54,910
Here there were royal red roses, and jasmine, and tall white lilies, and in the hedge by the gate, sweet-brier and deep-cupped white convolvulus.

63
00:06:54,910 --> 00:07:05,620
I think I saw then for the first time how lovely God's good world is, and ever since then, thank God, I have been seeing it more and more.

64
00:07:05,620 --> 00:07:08,780
That was a happy morning.

65
00:07:10,080 --> 00:07:15,540
The boys—whom I had not seen for ever so long, because of the measles—were up already.

66
00:07:15,540 --> 00:07:22,000
Alfred had a rabbit for me—a white rabbit with pink eyes—in a hutch he had made himself.

67
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:29,250
And Harry led me to a nook among the roots of the copper beech, where he showed me two dormice in an old tea-caddy.

68
00:07:29,250 --> 00:07:32,940
"You shall go shares in them if you like," he said.

69
00:07:32,940 --> 00:07:45,780
There was honey in the comb for breakfast, and new-laid eggs, and my mother was there in a cool cotton gown pouring out tea, and purring with pleasure at having all her kittens together again.

70
00:07:45,780 --> 00:07:54,460
There were cool raspberries on the table too, trimmed with fresh green leaves, and through the window we saw the fruit garden and its promise.

71
00:07:54,460 --> 00:07:57,610
That was summer indeed.

72
00:07:57,610 --> 00:08:03,280
After breakfast my mother called me to her—she had some patterns in her hand.

73
00:08:03,280 --> 00:08:07,120
"You must be measured for some new frocks, Daisy," she said.

74
00:08:07,120 --> 00:08:08,400
"Oh, how nice.

75
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:09,650
What colour?"

76
00:08:09,650 --> 00:08:13,760
"Well, some nice white ones, and this pretty plaid."

77
00:08:13,760 --> 00:08:16,580
She held up a pattern as she spoke.

78
00:08:16,580 --> 00:08:19,120
It was a Stuart plaid.

79
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:20,690
"Oh, not that!"

80
00:08:20,690 --> 00:08:21,740
I cried.

81
00:08:21,740 --> 00:08:23,810
"Not this pretty plaid, darling?

82
00:08:23,810 --> 00:08:25,580
Why not?"

83
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:29,860
If you'll believe me, I could not say why not.

84
00:08:29,860 --> 00:08:38,930
And the frock was made, and I wore it, loathing it, till the day when I fell out of the apple-tree, and it broke my fall by catching on a branch.

85
00:08:38,930 --> 00:08:48,240
But it saved my life at the expense of its own; and I gave a feast to all the dolls to celebrate its interment in the rag-bag.

86
00:08:48,240 --> 00:08:56,780
I have often wondered what it is that keeps children from telling their mothers these things—and even now I don't know.

87
00:08:56,780 --> 00:09:03,590
I only know I might have been saved many of these little-big troubles if I had only been able to explain.

88
00:09:03,590 --> 00:09:13,560
But I wasn't; and to this day my mother does not know how and why I hated that Stuart plaid frock.

89
00:09:13,560 --> 00:09:15,520
End of Part 1

