92
00:09:27,970 --> 00:09:31,560
PART 2
LONG DIVISION

93
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:42,500
I spent a year in the select boarding establishment for young ladies and gentlemen at Stamford, and I venture to think that I should have preferred a penal settlement.

94
00:09:42,500 --> 00:09:51,340
Miss Fairfield, whose school it was was tall and pale and dark, and I thought her as good and beautiful as an angel.

95
00:09:51,340 --> 00:09:56,390
I don't know now whether she was really beautiful, but I know she was good.

96
00:09:56,390 --> 00:10:05,310
And her mother—dear soul—had a sympathy with small folly in disgrace, which has written her name in gold letters on my heart.

97
00:10:05,310 --> 00:10:10,240
But there was another person in the house, whose name I will not put down.

98
00:10:10,240 --> 00:10:14,800
She came continually between me and my adored Miss Fairfield.

99
00:10:14,800 --> 00:10:22,020
She had a sort of influence over me which made it impossible for me ever to do anything well while she was near me.

100
00:10:22,020 --> 00:10:33,260
Miss Fairfield's health compelled her to leave much to Miss ——, and I was, in consequence, as gloomy a cynic as any child of my age in Lincolnshire.

101
00:10:33,260 --> 00:10:39,980
My chief troubles were three—my hair, my bands, and my arithmetic.

102
00:10:39,980 --> 00:10:43,850
My hair was never tidy—I don't know why.

103
00:10:43,850 --> 00:10:49,690
Perhaps it runs in the family—for my little daughter's head is just as rough as mine used to be.

104
00:10:49,690 --> 00:10:52,690
This got me into continual disgrace.

105
00:10:52,690 --> 00:11:01,720
I am sure I tried hard enough to keep it tidy—I brushed it for fruitless hours till my little head was so sore that it hurt me to put my hat on.

106
00:11:01,720 --> 00:11:09,970
But it never would look smooth and shiny, like Katie Martin's, nor would it curl prettily like the red locks of Cissy Thomas.

107
00:11:09,970 --> 00:11:13,810
It was always a rough, impossible brown mop.

108
00:11:13,810 --> 00:11:18,940
I got into a terrible scrape for trying to soften it by an invention of my own.

109
00:11:18,940 --> 00:11:26,810
As we all know, Burleigh House is by Stamford Town, and in Burleigh Park we children took our daily constitutional.

110
00:11:26,810 --> 00:11:37,250
We played under the big oaks there, and were bored to extinction, not because we disliked the park, but because we went there every day at the same hour.

111
00:11:37,250 --> 00:11:53,270
Now Harry Martin (he wore striped stockings and was always losing his handkerchief) suffered from his hair almost as much as I did; so when I unfolded my plan to him one day in the park, he joyfully agreed to help me.

112
00:11:53,270 --> 00:12:11,010
We each gathered a pocketful of acorns, and when we went to wash our hands before dinner, we cut up some of the acorns into little bits, and put them into the doll's bath with some cold water and a little scent that Cissy Thomas gave us, out of a bottle she had bought for twopence at the fair at home.

113
00:12:11,010 --> 00:12:16,780
"This," I said, "will be acorn oil—scented acorn oil."

114
00:12:16,780 --> 00:12:18,180
"Will it?"

115
00:12:18,180 --> 00:12:20,140
said Harry doubtfully.

116
00:12:20,140 --> 00:12:25,210
"Yes," I replied, adding confidently, "and there is nothing better for the hair."

117
00:12:25,210 --> 00:12:34,540
But we never had a chance of even seeing whether acorns and water would turn to oil—a miracle which I entirely believed in.

118
00:12:34,540 --> 00:12:43,340
The dinner-bell rang, and I only had time hastily to conceal the doll's bath at the back of the cupboard where Miss ——— kept her dresses.

119
00:12:43,340 --> 00:12:45,520
That was Saturday.

120
00:12:45,520 --> 00:12:56,860
Next day we found that Miss ——'s best dress (the blue silk with the Bismarck brown gimp) had slipped from its peg and fallen on to the doll's bath.

121
00:12:56,860 --> 00:13:09,330
The dress was ruined, and when Harry Martin and I owned up, as in honour bound—Miss Fairfield was away in London—we were deprived of dinner, and had a long Psalm to learn.

122
00:13:09,330 --> 00:13:19,140
I don't know whether punishment affects the hair, but I thought, next morning at prayers, that Harry's tow-crop looked more like bay than ever.

123
00:13:20,600 --> 00:13:29,890
My hands were more compromising to me than anyone would have believed who had ever seen their size, for, in the winter especially, they were never clean.

124
00:13:29,890 --> 00:13:40,790
I can see now the little willow-patterned basin of hard cold water, and smell the unpleasant little square of mottled soap with which I was expected to wash them.

125
00:13:40,790 --> 00:13:56,590
I don't know how the others managed, but for me the result was always the same—failure; and when I presented myself at breakfast, trying to hide my red and grubby little paws in my pinafore, Miss —— used to say:

126
00:13:56,590 --> 00:13:59,860
"Show your hands, Daisy—yes as I thought.

127
00:13:59,860 --> 00:14:02,460
Not fit to sit down with young ladies and gentlemen.

128
00:14:02,460 --> 00:14:04,570
Breakfast in the schoolroom for Miss Daisy."

129
00:14:04,570 --> 00:14:14,110
Then little Miss Daisy would shiveringly betake herself to the cold bare schoolroom, where the fire had but just been kindled.

130
00:14:14,110 --> 00:14:25,180
I used to sit cowering over the damp sticks with my white mug—mauve spotted it was I remember, and had a brown crack near the handle—on a chair beside me.

131
00:14:25,180 --> 00:14:36,680
Sometimes I used to pull a twig from the fire, harpoon my bread-and-butter with it, and hold it to the fire: the warm, pale, greasy result I called toast.

132
00:14:36,680 --> 00:14:41,730
All this happened when Miss Fairfield was laid up with bronchitis.

133
00:14:41,730 --> 00:14:47,250
It was at that time, too, that my battle with compound long division began.

134
00:14:47,250 --> 00:14:57,730
Now I was not, I think, a very dull child, and always had an indignant sense that I could do sums well enough if any one would tell me what they meant.

135
00:14:57,730 --> 00:15:08,210
But no one did, and day after day the long division sums, hopelessly wrong, disfigured my slate, and were washed off with my tears.

136
00:15:08,210 --> 00:15:14,820
Day after day I was sent to bed, my dinner was knocked off, or my breakfast, or my tea.

137
00:15:14,820 --> 00:15:20,370
I should literally have starved, I do believe, but for dear Mrs. Fairfield.

138
00:15:20,370 --> 00:15:30,020
She kept my little Body going with illicit cakes and plums and the like, and fed my starving little heart with surreptitious kisses and kind words.

139
00:15:30,020 --> 00:15:36,180
She would lie in wait for me as I passed down the hall, and in a whisper call me into the store closet.

140
00:15:36,180 --> 00:15:49,320
It had a mingled and delicious smell of pickles and tea and oranges and jam, and the one taper Mrs. Fairfield carried only lighted dimly the delightful mystery of its well-filled shelves.

141
00:15:49,320 --> 00:15:58,620
Mrs. Fairfield used to give me a great lump of cake or a broad slice of bread and jam, and lock me into the dark cupboard till it was eaten.

142
00:15:58,620 --> 00:16:14,850
I never taste black-currant jam now without a strong memory of the dark hole of happiness, where I used to wait—my sticky fingers held well away from my pinafore—till Mrs. Fairfield's heavy step and jingling keys came to release me.

143
00:16:14,850 --> 00:16:25,380
Then she would sponge my hands and face and send me away clean, replete, and with a better heart for the eternal conflict with long division.

144
00:16:26,600 --> 00:16:37,420
I fancy that when Miss Fairfield came downstairs again she changed the field of my arithmetical studies; for during the spring I seem to remember a blessed respite from my troubles.

145
00:16:37,420 --> 00:16:42,910
It is true that Miss ——— was away, staying with friends.

146
00:16:42,910 --> 00:16:57,280
I was very popular at school that term I remember, for I had learned to make dolls' bedsteads out of match-boxes during the holidays, and my eldest sister's Christmas present provided me with magnificent hangings for the same.

147
00:16:57,280 --> 00:17:06,460
Imagine a vivid green silk sash, with brilliant butterflies embroidered all over it in coloured silk and gold thread.

148
00:17:06,460 --> 00:17:12,790
A long sash, too, from which one could well spare a few inches at a time for upholstery.

149
00:17:12,790 --> 00:17:25,660
I acquired many marbles, and much gingerbread, and totally eclipsed Cissy Thomas who bad enjoyed the fleeting sunshine of popular favour on the insecure basis of paper dolls.

150
00:17:25,660 --> 00:17:48,500
Over my memory of this term no long division cast its hateful shade, and the scolding my dear mother gave me when she saw my sashes' fair proportions docked to a waistband and a hard knot, with two brief and irregular ends, was so gentle that I endured it with fortitude, and considered my ten weeks of popularity cheaply bought.

151
00:17:48,500 --> 00:17:57,260
I went back to school in high spirits with a new set of sashes and some magnificent pieces of silk and lace from my mother's lavendered wardrobe.

152
00:17:57,260 --> 00:18:12,620
But no one wanted dolls' beds anymore; and Cissy Thomas had brought back a herbarium: the others all became botanists, and I, after a faint effort to emulate their successes, fell back on my garden.

153
00:18:12,620 --> 00:18:23,620
The seeds I had set in the spring had had a rest during the Easter holidays, and were already sprouting greenly, but alas, I never saw them flower.

154
00:18:23,620 --> 00:18:26,610
Long division set in again.

155
00:18:26,610 --> 00:18:45,200
Again, day after day, I sat lonely in the schoolroom—now like a furnace—and ate my dry bread and milk and water in the depths of disgrace, with the faux commencements and those revolting sums staring at me from my tear-blotted slate.

156
00:18:45,200 --> 00:18:56,190
Night after night I cried myself to sleep in my bed—whose coarse home-spun sheets were hotter than blankets—because I could not get the answers right.

157
00:18:56,190 --> 00:19:06,440
Even Miss Fairfield, I fancied, began to look coldly on me, and the other children naturally did not care to associate with one so deficient in arithmetic.

158
00:19:06,440 --> 00:19:23,100
One evening as I was sitting as usual sucking the smooth, dark slate pencil, and grieving over my troubles with the heart-broken misery of a child, to whom the present grief looks eternal, I heard a carriage drive up to the door.

159
00:19:23,100 --> 00:19:43,150
Our schoolroom was at the back, and I was too much interested in a visitor—especially one who came at that hour and in a carriage—to be able to bear the suspense of that silent schoolroom, so I cautiously opened its door and crept on hands and knees across the passage and looked down through the bannisters.

160
00:19:43,150 --> 00:19:45,240
They were opening the door.

161
00:19:45,240 --> 00:19:50,330
It was a lady, and Mrs. Fairfield came out of the dining-room to meet her.

162
00:19:50,330 --> 00:19:56,310
It was a lady in a black moire antique dress and Paisley shawl of the then mode.

163
00:19:56,310 --> 00:20:10,220
It was a lady whose face I could not see, because her back was to the red sunset light; but at that moment she spoke, and the next I was clinging round the moue skirts with my bead buried in the Paisley shawl.

164
00:20:10,220 --> 00:20:15,230
The world, all upside down, had suddenly righted itself.

165
00:20:15,230 --> 00:20:25,010
I, who had faced it alone, now looked out at it from the secure shelter of a moiré screen—for my mother had come to see me.

166
00:20:25,010 --> 00:20:30,450
I did not cry myself to sleep that night, because my head lay on her arm.

167
00:20:30,450 --> 00:20:35,760
But even then I could not express bow wretched I had been.

168
00:20:35,760 --> 00:21:07,490
Only when I heard that my mother was going to the South of France with my sisters, I clung about her neck, and with such insistence implored her not to leave me—not to go without me, that I think I must have expressed my trouble without uttering it, for when, after three delicious days of drives and walks, in which I had always a loving hand to hold, my mother left Stamford, she took me—trembling with joy like a prisoner reprieved—with her.

169
00:21:07,490 --> 00:21:13,420
And I have never seen—or wished to see—Stamford again.

170
00:21:14,760 --> 00:21:16,700
End of Part 2

