PART 3
SOUTH WITH THE SWALLOWS

174
00:21:35,580 --> 00:21:43,540
With what delicious thrills of anticipation and excitement I packed my doll's clothes on the eve of our journey!

175
00:21:43,540 --> 00:21:57,350
I had a little tin trunk with a real padlock; I have it still, by the way, only now it holds old letters and a bunch of violets and a few other little worthless things that I do not often have the courage to look at nowadays.

176
00:21:57,350 --> 00:22:07,360
It is battered now and the paint is worn off; but then it was fresh and shiny and I packed all the doll's clothes in it with a light heart.

177
00:22:07,360 --> 00:22:23,480
I don't remember anything about our leaving home, or saying good-bye to the boys; so I fancy that they must have gone back to school some time before; but I remember the night passage from Newhaven to Dieppe far too vividly to care to describe it.

178
00:22:23,480 --> 00:22:32,010
I was a very worn-out little girl indeed when we reached Rouen and I lay for the first time in a little white French bed.

179
00:22:32,010 --> 00:23:01,860
My mind was, I suppose, a little upset by my soul's sorrows at Stamford and my body's unspeakable discomforts on board the channel boat, and I was seized with a horror of the words Débit de Tabac which I had noticed on our way from the station; I associated them with the gravestone of my father, I don't know why, I can only conjecture that the last syllable of Débit being the same as that of our name, may have had something to do with it.

180
00:23:01,860 --> 00:23:10,890
I lay awake in the dark, the light from the oil lamp in the street came through the Persiennes and fell in bright bars on the wall.

181
00:23:10,890 --> 00:23:18,350
As I grew drowsier I seemed to read there in letters of fire "Débit de Tabac"

182
00:23:18,350 --> 00:23:30,690
Then I fell asleep, and dreamed that my father's ghost came to me, and implored me to have the horrible French inscription erased from his tomb—"for I was an Englishman," he said.

183
00:23:30,690 --> 00:23:40,150
Then I woke, rigid with terror, and finally summoned courage to creep across the corridor to my mother's room and seek refuge in her arms.

184
00:23:40,150 --> 00:23:48,500
I am particular to mention this dream because it is the first remembrance I have of any terror of the dead, or of the supernatural.

185
00:23:48,500 --> 00:23:55,280
I do not at all know how it had its rise; perhaps in the chatter of some nurse-maid, long forgotten.

186
00:23:55,280 --> 00:24:06,860
By-and-by I should like to tell you about some of the things that used to frighten me when I was a child; but just now we are at Rouen where Joan of Arc was burned and where the church of St.

187
00:24:06,860 --> 00:24:08,090
Ouen is.

188
00:24:08,090 --> 00:24:16,870
Even then the beauty of that marvellous Gothic church filled me with a delight none the less intense for being incomprehensible to me.

189
00:24:16,870 --> 00:24:18,790
We went too, to St.

190
00:24:18,790 --> 00:24:20,820
Catharine du Mont.

191
00:24:20,820 --> 00:24:23,880
The ceiling of the church was blue, with gold stars.

192
00:24:23,880 --> 00:24:26,010
I thought it very beautiful.

193
00:24:26,010 --> 00:24:35,730
It was very windy on the mount, I remember, and the sky outside was blue, like the church ceiling, with white clouds instead of gold stars.

194
00:24:35,730 --> 00:24:44,230
There was a stall a little way clown the hill where a white-coifed woman sold crucifixes and medals and rosaries and pictures.

195
00:24:44,230 --> 00:24:48,690
My mother bought me a little painting of the church in an alabaster frame.

196
00:24:48,690 --> 00:24:52,640
It was for a long time one of my chief treasures.

197
00:24:52,640 --> 00:24:55,030
We went on to Paris.

198
00:24:55,030 --> 00:24:57,710
It was very hot and very dusty.

199
00:24:57,710 --> 00:25:00,130
It was the Exhibition year.

200
00:25:00,130 --> 00:25:06,110
I went to the Exhibition which seemed to me large, empty and very tiring.

201
00:25:06,110 --> 00:25:11,230
I saw the Emperor and the pretty Empress driving in a carriage with their little son.

202
00:25:11,230 --> 00:25:16,920
The boy was about my own age, and wore a velvet suit and an embroidered frilly collar.

203
00:25:16,920 --> 00:25:20,560
The crowd cheered them with wild enthusiasm.

204
00:25:20,560 --> 00:25:25,380
Three years later— But this is not a history-paper.

205
00:25:25,380 --> 00:25:31,450
The pleasantest part of our stay in Paris was the time that my cousin Fred spent with us.

206
00:25:31,450 --> 00:25:35,830
He lived in Paris, and knew that little girls like sweeties.

207
00:25:35,830 --> 00:25:45,760
Also he sang the comic songs of the day, "Kafoozleum" and "It's really very unpleasant," and taught me their long and dreary words.

208
00:25:45,760 --> 00:25:51,970
He was very kind to me, and I remember him with tenderness though I have never seen him since.

209
00:25:51,970 --> 00:26:04,200
On the whole, though I had a real silver daisy brooch bought at the Exhibition, and more toys than could conveniently be carried in my tin trunk, I was glad to get away from Paris.

210
00:26:04,200 --> 00:26:11,370
As this is not a guide-book I suppose I must not tell you about Tours, and the Convent of Marmoutier.

211
00:26:11,370 --> 00:26:29,880
I expected a convent to be a dark and terrible place, with perhaps a nun or two being built into the wall, and I was relieved to find a trim, well-kept garden and a pleasant house, where kindly-faced women in black gowns and white guimpes walked about breviary in hand.

212
00:26:29,880 --> 00:26:41,410
Nor must I linger at Poitiers, where we saw gloves made, and I, to my intense delight was measured for a small pair of bright blue kid.

213
00:26:41,410 --> 00:26:47,220
I liked Poitiers—especially the old Byzantine church now used as a stable.

214
00:26:47,220 --> 00:26:50,770
I picked up a bone there, and treasured it for months.

215
00:26:50,770 --> 00:27:02,020
It was human, I was convinced, and I wove many romances round the little brown relic-romances that considerably embittered the reality when I came to know it.

216
00:27:02,020 --> 00:27:03,670
"What's that?"

217
00:27:03,670 --> 00:27:10,100
Alfred asked picking the bone from its resting place in cotton-wool in my corner drawer months afterwards.

218
00:27:10,100 --> 00:27:13,800
"A human bone," I said gravely.

219
00:27:13,800 --> 00:27:17,350
Alfred roared with aggravating laughter.

220
00:27:17,350 --> 00:27:20,940
"It's only half a fowl's back—you little silly."

221
00:27:20,940 --> 00:27:29,410
Ashamed and confused I flung the bone into the inmost recesses of the drawer, and assured him that he was mistaken.

222
00:27:29,410 --> 00:27:31,800
But he wasn't.

223
00:27:33,180 --> 00:27:45,230
We went from Poitiers to Angoulème—how often in school I have got into trouble for tracing that route on the map of France when I should have been tracing Cap Griz Nez, or the course of the Rhone!

224
00:27:45,230 --> 00:27:49,990
And so, by easy, stages we reached Bordeaux.

225
00:27:49,990 --> 00:27:55,060
Bordeaux was en fête—the great annual fair was in progress.

226
00:27:55,060 --> 00:28:00,620
The big market-place was covered with booths filled with the most fascinating objects.

227
00:28:00,620 --> 00:28:07,500
I was very happy at Bordeaux until it occurred to some one to take me to see the mummies.

228
00:28:07,500 --> 00:28:13,520
After that, "Farewell the tranquil mind, farewell content."

229
00:28:13,520 --> 00:28:23,340
And here I cannot resist the temptation to put a long parenthesis in my traveller's tale, and to write a little about what used to frighten me when I was little.

230
00:28:23,340 --> 00:28:28,630
And then I shall tell you about my first experience of learning French.

231
00:28:28,630 --> 00:28:31,760
End of Part 3

