234
00:28:44,300 --> 00:28:48,060
PART 4
IN THE DARK

235
00:28:48,060 --> 00:29:11,510
How can I write of it, sitting here in the shifting shade of the lime-trees, with the sunny daisied grass stretching away to the border where the hollyhocks and lilies and columbines are, my ears filled with the soft swish-swish of the gardener's scythe at the other end of the garden, and the merry little voices of the children away in the meadow?

236
00:29:11,510 --> 00:29:30,780
Only by shutting my eyes and ears to the sweet sounds and sights of summer and the sun can I recall at all for you the dead silences, the frozen terrors of the long, dark nights when I was little, and lonely, and very very much afraid.

237
00:29:31,780 --> 00:29:40,860
The first thing I remember that frightened me was running into my father's dressing-room and finding him playing at wild beasts with my brothers.

238
00:29:40,860 --> 00:29:47,590
He wore his great fur travelling coat inside out, and his roars were completely convincing.

239
00:29:47,590 --> 00:29:54,190
I was borne away screaming, and dreamed of wild beasts for many a long night afterwards.

240
00:29:54,190 --> 00:29:57,450
Then came some nursery charades.

241
00:29:57,450 --> 00:30:07,990
I was the high-born orphan, whom gipsies were to steal, and my part was to lie in a cradle, and, at the proper moment to be carried away shrieking.

242
00:30:07,990 --> 00:30:15,150
I understood my part perfectly—I was about three, I suppose—and had rehearsed it more than once.

243
00:30:15,150 --> 00:30:24,460
Being carried off in the arms of the gipsy (my favourite sister) was nothing to scream at, I thought, but she told me to scream, and I did it.

244
00:30:24,460 --> 00:30:48,980
Unfortunately, however, there had been no dress rehearsals, and when, on the night of the performance the high-born orphan found itself close to a big black bonnet and a hideous mask, it did scream to some purpose, and presently screaming itself into some sort of fit or swoon, was put to bed, and stayed there for many days which passed dreamlike.

245
00:30:48,980 --> 00:30:55,160
But that old woman haunted my dreams for years—haunts them still indeed.

246
00:30:55,160 --> 00:30:58,770
I tell you I come across her in my dreams to this day.

247
00:30:58,770 --> 00:31:11,280
She bends over me and puts her face close to mine, and I wake with a spasm of agonised terror; only now it is not horrible to me to waken "in the dark."

248
00:31:11,280 --> 00:31:18,960
I draw a few long breaths and as soon as my heart beats a little less wildly I fall asleep again.

249
00:31:18,960 --> 00:31:24,640
But a child who wakes from an ugly dream does not fall asleep so quickly.

250
00:31:24,640 --> 00:31:35,210
For to a child who is frightened, the darkness and the silence of its lonely room are only a shade less terrible than the wild horrors of dreamland.

251
00:31:35,210 --> 00:31:53,280
One used to lie awake in the silence, listening, listening to the pad-pad of one's heart, straining one's ears to make sure that it was not the pad-pad of something else, something unspeakable creeping towards one out of the horrible dense dark.

252
00:31:53,280 --> 00:32:01,110
One used to lie quite, quite still, I remember, listening, listening.

253
00:32:01,110 --> 00:32:08,580
And when my nurse came to bed and tucked me up, she used to find my pillow wet, and say to the under-nurse —

254
00:32:08,580 --> 00:32:10,050
"Weakness, you know.

255
00:32:10,050 --> 00:32:13,120
The precious poppet doesn't seem to get any stronger."

256
00:32:13,120 --> 00:32:16,740
But my pillow was not wet with tears of weakness.

257
00:32:16,740 --> 00:32:20,340
These were the dews of agony and terror.

258
00:32:20,340 --> 00:32:30,860
My nurse—ah, how good she was to me—never went downstairs to supper after she found out my terrors which she very quickly did.

259
00:32:30,860 --> 00:32:42,430
She used to sit in the day nursery with the door open "a tiny crack," and that light was company, because I knew I had only to call out, and someone who loved me would come and banish fear.

260
00:32:42,430 --> 00:32:50,310
But a light without human companionship was worse than darkness, especially a little light.

261
00:32:50,310 --> 00:33:05,800
Night-lights, deepening the shadows with their horrid possibilities are a mere refinement of cruelty, and some friends who thought to do me a kindness by leaving the gas burning low gave me one of the most awful nights I ever had.

262
00:33:05,800 --> 00:33:16,500
It was a strange house in Sutherland Gardens—a house with large rooms and heavy hangings—with massive wardrobes and deep ottoman boxes.

263
00:33:16,500 --> 00:33:24,680
The immense four-post beds stood out about a yard from the wall, for some "convenience of sweeping" reason, I believe.

264
00:33:24,680 --> 00:33:58,630
Consider the horror of having behind you, as you lay trembling in the chill linen of a strange bed, a dark space, no comforting solid wall that you could put your hand up to and touch, but a dark space, from which, even now, in the black silence something might be stealthily creeping—something which would presently lean over you, in the dark-whose touch you would feel, not knowing whether it were the old woman in the mask or some new terror.

265
00:33:58,630 --> 00:34:02,130
That was the torture of the first night.

266
00:34:02,130 --> 00:34:06,490
The next I begged that the gas might be left "full on."

267
00:34:06,490 --> 00:34:11,050
It was, and I fell asleep in comparative security.

268
00:34:11,050 --> 00:34:18,830
But while I slept, came some thrifty soul, and finding the gas "burning to waste" turned it down.

269
00:34:18,830 --> 00:34:22,480
Not out—down.

270
00:34:23,520 --> 00:34:31,860
I awoke in a faint light, and presently sat up in bed to see where it came from, and this is what I saw.

271
00:34:31,860 --> 00:34:42,270
A corpse laid out under white draperies, and at its foot a skeleton with luminous skull and outstretched bony arm.

272
00:34:42,270 --> 00:35:00,550
I knew, somewhere far away and deep down, my reason knew that the dead body was a white dress laid on a long ottoman, that the skull was the opal globe of the gas and the arm the pipe of the gas-bracket, but that was not reason's hour.

273
00:35:00,550 --> 00:35:14,020
Imagination held sway, and her poor little victim, who was ten years old then, and ought to have renown better, sat up in bed, hour after hour, with the shadowy void behind lien.

274
00:35:14,020 --> 00:35:19,720
The dark curtains on each side, and in front that horror.

275
00:35:19,720 --> 00:35:25,800
Next day I went home, which was perhaps a good thing for my brain.

276
00:35:27,220 --> 00:35:34,780
When my father was alive we lived in a big house in Kennington Lane, where he taught young men agriculture and chemistry.

277
00:35:34,780 --> 00:35:39,710
My father had a big meadow and garden, and had a sort of small farm there.

278
00:35:39,710 --> 00:35:42,350
Fancy a farm in Kennington!

279
00:35:42,350 --> 00:35:47,320
Among the increase that blessed his shed was a two-headed calf.

280
00:35:47,320 --> 00:35:56,120
The head and shoulders of this were stuffed, and inspired me with a terror which my brothers increased by pursuing me with the terrible object.

281
00:35:56,120 --> 00:36:09,610
But one of my father's pupils to whom I owe that and many other kindnesses, one day seized me under one arm and the two-headed horror under the other, and thus equipped we pursued my brothers.

282
00:36:09,610 --> 00:36:13,950
They fled shrieking, and I never feared it again.

283
00:36:13,950 --> 00:36:25,250
In a dank stone-flagged room where the boots were blacked, and the more unwieldy chemicals housed, there was nailed on the wall the black skin of an emu.

284
00:36:25,250 --> 00:36:33,370
That skin, with its wiry black feathers that fluttered dismally in the draught, was no mere bird's skin to me.

285
00:36:33,370 --> 00:36:36,930
It hated me, it wished me ill.

286
00:36:36,930 --> 00:36:41,470
It was always lurking for me in the dark, ready to rush out at me.

287
00:36:41,470 --> 00:36:51,330
It was waiting for me at the top of the flight, while the old woman with the mask stretched skinny hands out to grasp my little legs as I went up the nursery stairs.

288
00:36:51,330 --> 00:36:55,730
I never passed the skin without covering my eyes with my hands.

289
00:36:55,730 --> 00:37:03,560
From this terror that walked by night I was delivered by Mr. Kearns, now public analyst for Sheffield.

290
00:37:03,560 --> 00:37:12,570
He took me on his shoulder, where I felt quite safe, reluctant but not resisting, to within a couple of yards of the emu.

291
00:37:12,570 --> 00:37:16,880
"Now," he said, "will you do what I tell you?"

292
00:37:16,880 --> 00:37:20,810
"Not any nearer," I said evasively.

293
00:37:20,810 --> 00:37:23,550
"Now you know I won't let it hurt you."

294
00:37:23,550 --> 00:37:24,990
"Yes."

295
00:37:24,990 --> 00:37:28,560
"Then will you stroke it, if I do first?"

296
00:37:28,560 --> 00:37:30,870
I didn't want to.

297
00:37:30,870 --> 00:37:33,060
"To please me."

298
00:37:33,060 --> 00:37:37,200
That argument was conclusive, for I loved him.

299
00:37:37,200 --> 00:37:44,790
Then we approached the black feathers, I clinging desperately to his neck, and sobbing convulsively.

300
00:37:44,790 --> 00:37:47,170
"No-no-no-not any nearer!"

301
00:37:47,170 --> 00:37:51,940
But he was kind and wise, and insisted.

302
00:37:51,940 --> 00:37:55,750
His big hand smoothed down the feathers.

303
00:37:55,750 --> 00:37:57,470
"Now, Daisy.

304
00:37:57,470 --> 00:37:58,820
You know you promised.

305
00:37:58,820 --> 00:38:00,800
Give me your hand."

306
00:38:00,800 --> 00:38:07,310
I shut my eyes tight, and let him draw my hand down the dusty feathers.

307
00:38:07,310 --> 00:38:10,680
Then I opened my eyes a little bit.

308
00:38:10,680 --> 00:38:12,740
"Now you stroke it.

309
00:38:12,740 --> 00:38:14,850
Stroke the poor emu."

310
00:38:14,850 --> 00:38:16,710
I did so.

311
00:38:16,710 --> 00:38:18,900
"Are you afraid now?"

312
00:38:18,900 --> 00:38:22,250
Curiously enough I wasn't.

313
00:38:22,250 --> 00:38:25,500
Poor Mr. Kearns paid dearly for his kindness.

314
00:38:25,500 --> 00:38:34,980
For several weeks I gave him no peace, but insisted on being taken, at all hours of the day and night to "stroke the poor emu."

315
00:38:34,980 --> 00:38:38,420
So proud is one of a new courage.

316
00:38:39,520 --> 00:38:51,000
After we left Kennington, I seem to have had a period of more ordinary terrors-of dreams from which to awaken was mere relief; not a horror scarcely less than that of the dream itself.

317
00:38:51,000 --> 00:38:56,860
I dreamed of cows and dogs, of falling houses, and crumbling precipices.

318
00:38:56,860 --> 00:39:05,380
It was not till that night at Rouen that the old horror of the dark came back, deepened by superstitious dread.

319
00:39:05,380 --> 00:39:09,110
But all this time I have not told you about the mummies at Bordeaux.

320
00:39:09,110 --> 00:39:11,870
And now there is no room for them here.

321
00:39:11,870 --> 00:39:14,640
They must go into the next chapter.

322
00:39:15,640 --> 00:39:17,580
End of Part 4

