325
00:39:29,910 --> 00:39:34,320
PART 5
THE MUMMIES AT BORDEAUX

326
00:39:35,480 --> 00:39:49,770
It was because I was tired of churches and picture-galleries, of fairs and markets, of the strange babble of foreign tongues and the thin English of the guide-book, that I begged so hard to be taken to see the mummies.

327
00:39:49,770 --> 00:39:54,170
To me the name of a mummy was as a friend's name.

328
00:39:54,170 --> 00:40:08,900
As one Englishman travelling across a desert seeks to find another of whom he has heard in that far land, so I sought to meet these mummies who had cousins at home, in the British Museum, in dear, dear England.

329
00:40:08,900 --> 00:40:24,060
My fancy did not paint mummies for me apart from plate-glass cases, camphor, boarded galleries, and kindly curators, and I longed to see them as I longed to see home, and to hear my own tongue spoken about me.

330
00:40:24,060 --> 00:40:32,700
I was consumed by a fever of impatience for the three days which had to go by before the coming of the day on which the treasures might be visited.

331
00:40:32,700 --> 00:40:42,630
My sisters who were to lead me to these delights, believed too that the mummies would be chiefly interesting on account of their association with Bloomsbury.

332
00:40:42,630 --> 00:40:56,060
Well, we went—I in my best blue silk frock, which I insisted on wearing to honour the occasion, holding the hand of my sister and positively skipping with delicious anticipation.

333
00:40:56,060 --> 00:41:02,350
There was some delay about keys, during which my excitement was scarcely to be restrained.

334
00:41:02,350 --> 00:41:11,880
Then we went through an arched doorway and along a flagged passage, the old man who guided us explaining volubly in French as we went.

335
00:41:11,880 --> 00:41:13,220
"What does he say?"

336
00:41:13,220 --> 00:41:15,730
"He says they are natural mummies."

337
00:41:15,730 --> 00:41:18,140
"What does that mean?"

338
00:41:18,140 --> 00:41:25,760
"They are not embalmed by man, like the Egyptian ones, but simply by the peculiar earth of the churchyard where they were buried."

339
00:41:26,820 --> 00:41:32,850
The words did not touch my conception of the glass cases and their good-natured guardian.

340
00:41:32,850 --> 00:41:35,880
The passage began to slope downward.

341
00:41:35,880 --> 00:41:41,580
A chill air breathed on our faces, bringing with it a damp earthy smell.

342
00:41:41,580 --> 00:41:44,510
Then we came to some narrow stone steps.

343
00:41:44,510 --> 00:41:46,550
Our guide spoke again.

344
00:41:46,550 --> 00:41:48,600
"What does he say?"

345
00:41:48,600 --> 00:41:52,980
"We are to be careful, the steps are slippery and mouldy."

346
00:41:52,980 --> 00:42:06,010
I think even then my expectation still was of a long clean gallery, filled with the white light of a London noon, shed through high skylights on Egyptian treasures.

347
00:42:06,010 --> 00:42:10,580
But the stairs were dark, and I held my sister's hand tightly.

348
00:42:10,580 --> 00:42:13,920
Down we went, down, down!

349
00:42:13,920 --> 00:42:16,020
"What does he say?"

350
00:42:16,020 --> 00:42:19,650
"We are under the church now; these are the vaults."

351
00:42:19,650 --> 00:42:28,560
We went along another passage, the damp mouldy smell increasing, and my clasp of my sister's hand grew closer and closer.

352
00:42:28,560 --> 00:42:37,290
We stopped in front of a heavy door barred with iron, and our guide turned a big reluctant key in a lock that grated.

353
00:42:37,290 --> 00:42:44,260
"Les voila," he said, throwing open the door and drawing back dramatically.

354
00:42:45,480 --> 00:42:50,850
We were in the room before my sisters had time to see cause for regretting that they had brought me.

355
00:42:50,850 --> 00:42:59,390
The vision of dry boards and white light and glass cases vanished, and in its stead I saw this:

356
00:42:59,390 --> 00:43:14,140
A small vault, as my memory serves me, about fifteen feet square, with an arched roof, from the centre of which hung a lamp that burned with a faint blue light, and made the guide's candle look red and lurid.

357
00:43:14,140 --> 00:43:19,200
The floor was flagged like the passages, and was as damp and chill.

358
00:43:19,200 --> 00:43:32,010
Round three sides of the room ran a railing, and behind it—standing against the wall, with a ghastly look of life in death—were about two hundred skeletons.

359
00:43:32,010 --> 00:43:52,590
Not white clean skeletons, hung on wires, like the one yon see at the doctor's, but skeletons with the flesh hardened on their bones, with their long dry hair hanging on each side of their brown faces, where the skin in drying had drawn itself back from their gleaming teeth and empty eye-sockets.

360
00:43:52,590 --> 00:44:03,770
Skeletons draped in mouldering shreds of shrouds and grave-clothes, their lean fingers still clothed with dry skin, seemed to reach out towards me.

361
00:44:03,770 --> 00:44:14,950
There they stood, men, women, and children, knee-deep in loose bones collected from the other vaults of the church, and heaped round them.

362
00:44:14,950 --> 00:44:22,200
On the wall near the door I saw the dried body of a little child hung up by its hair.

363
00:44:23,540 --> 00:44:27,660
I don't think I screamed or cried, or even said a word.

364
00:44:27,660 --> 00:44:44,860
I think I was paralysed with horror, but I remember presently going back up those stairs, holding tightly to that kindly hand, and not daring to turn my head lest one of those charnel-house faces should peep out at me from some niche in the damp wall.

365
00:44:44,860 --> 00:44:59,950
It must have been late afternoon, and in the hurry of dressing for the table d'hote my stupor of fright must have passed unnoticed, for the next thing I remember is being alone in a large room, waiting as usual for my supper to be sent up.

366
00:44:59,950 --> 00:45:09,220
For my mother did not approve of late dinners for little people, and I was accustomed to have bread-and-milk alone while she and my sisters dined.

367
00:45:09,220 --> 00:45:15,800
It was a large room, and very imperfectly lighted by the two wax candles in silver candlesticks.

368
00:45:15,800 --> 00:45:20,380
There were two windows and a curtained alcove, where the beds were.

369
00:45:20,380 --> 00:45:23,490
Suddenly my blood ran cold.

370
00:45:23,490 --> 00:45:25,990
What was behind that curtain?

371
00:45:25,990 --> 00:45:27,680
Beds.

372
00:45:27,680 --> 00:45:34,420
"Yes," whispered something that was I, and yet not I; "but suppose there are no beds there now.

373
00:45:34,420 --> 00:45:38,410
Only mummies, mummies, mummies!"

374
00:45:38,410 --> 00:45:42,470
A sudden noise; I screamed with terror.

375
00:45:42,470 --> 00:45:46,250
It was only the door opening to let the waiter in.

376
00:45:46,250 --> 00:45:55,450
He was a young waiter. hardly more than a boy, and had always smiled kindly at me when we met, though hitherto our intercourse had not gone farther.

377
00:45:55,450 --> 00:46:03,160
Now I rushed to him and flung my arms round him, to his immense amazement and the near ruin of my bread and milk.

378
00:46:03,160 --> 00:46:12,920
He spoke no English and I no French, but somehow he managed to understand that I was afraid, and afraid of that curtained alcove.

379
00:46:14,160 --> 00:46:26,230
He set down the bread and milk, and be took me in his arms and together we fetched more candles, and then he drew back the awful curtain, and showed me the beds lying white and quiet.

380
00:46:26,230 --> 00:46:29,420
If I could have spoken French I should have said:

381
00:46:29,420 --> 00:46:35,740
"Yes; but how do I know it was all like that just now, before you drew the curtain back?"

382
00:46:36,980 --> 00:46:41,040
As it was I said nothing, only clung to his neck.

383
00:46:42,360 --> 00:46:49,750
I hope he did not get into any trouble that night for neglected duties, for he did not attempt to leave me until my mother came back.

384
00:46:49,750 --> 00:46:59,990
He sat down with me on his knee and petted me and sang to me under his breath, and fed me with the bread and milk, when by-and-by I grew calm enough to take it.

385
00:46:59,990 --> 00:47:03,370
All good things be with him wherever he is!

386
00:47:03,370 --> 00:47:12,810
I like best to think of him in a little hotel of his own, a quiet little country inn standing back from a straight road bordered with apple trees and poplars.

387
00:47:12,810 --> 00:47:26,290
There are wooden benches outside the door, and within a whitewashed kitchen, where a plump rosy-faced woman is busy with many cares—never busy enough, however, to pass the master of the house without a loving word or a loving look.

388
00:47:26,290 --> 00:47:44,900
I like to believe that now he has little children of his own, who hold out their arms when he opens the door, and who climb upon his knees clamouring for those same songs which be sang, out of the kindness of his boyish heart, to the little frightened English child, such a long, long time ago.

389
00:47:46,440 --> 00:48:01,830
The mummies of Bordeaux were the crowning horror of my childish life; it is to them, I think, more than to any other thing, that I owe nights and nights of anguish and horror, long years of bitterest fear and dread.

390
00:48:01,830 --> 00:48:10,260
All the other fears could have been effaced but the shock of that sight branded it on my brain, and I never forgot it.

391
00:48:10,260 --> 00:48:29,220
For many years I could not bring myself to go about any house in the dark, and long after I was a grown woman I was tortured, in the dark watches, by imagination and memory, who rose strong and united, overpowering my will and my reason as utterly as in my baby days.

392
00:48:29,220 --> 00:48:41,710
It was not till I had two little children of my own that I was able to conquer this mortal terror of darkness, and teach imagination her place, under the foot of reason and the will.

393
00:48:41,710 --> 00:48:46,460
My children, I resolved, should never know such fear.

394
00:48:46,460 --> 00:48:51,090
And to guard them from it I must banish it from my own soul.

395
00:48:51,090 --> 00:48:54,460
It was not easy, but it was done.

396
00:48:54,460 --> 00:49:00,040
It is banished now, and my babies, thank God, have never known it.

397
00:49:00,040 --> 00:49:23,370
It was a dark cloud that overshadowed my childhood, and I don't believe my mother ever knew how dark it was, for I could not tell anyone the full horror of it while it was over me; and when it had passed I came from it, as one who has lived long years in an enchanter's castle, where the sun is darkened always, might come forth into the splendour of noontide.

398
00:49:23,370 --> 00:49:39,340
Such an one breathes God's sweet air and beholds the free heavens with joyous leaps of heart; but he does not speak soon nor lightly of what befell in the dark, in the evil days, in the Castle of the Enchanter.

399
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:43,080
End of Part 5

