402
00:49:55,310 --> 00:49:57,700
PART 6

403
00:49:58,900 --> 00:50:02,110
She was the most beautiful person in the world.

404
00:50:02,110 --> 00:50:09,610
She had brown eyes and pink cheeks, a blue silk dress and a white bonnet with orange-blossoms in it.

405
00:50:09,610 --> 00:50:17,150
She had two pairs of shoes and two pairs of stockings, and she had two wigs, a brown and a flaxen one.

406
00:50:17,150 --> 00:50:22,350
All her clothes took off and on, and there was a complete change of them.

407
00:50:22,350 --> 00:50:32,780
I saw her first at a bazaar and longed to possess her, but her price was two guineas, and no hope mingled with my longing.

408
00:50:32,780 --> 00:50:38,610
Here let me make a confession, I had never really loved a doll.

409
00:50:38,610 --> 00:50:53,310
My affections up to that time had been lavished on a black and white spotted penny rabbit, bought at a Kentish fair; but when I saw Rénee, it seemed to me that if I could love a doll, this would be the one.

410
00:50:53,310 --> 00:50:57,280
We were at Pau then in a "select boarding-house."

411
00:50:57,280 --> 00:51:13,370
I was bored with travel, as I believe all children are—so large a part of a child's life is made up of little familiar playthings and objects; it has little of that historic and artistic sense which lends colour and delight to travel.

412
00:51:13,370 --> 00:51:19,150
I was tired of wandering about, and glad to think we were to stay in Pau for the winter.

413
00:51:19,150 --> 00:51:21,190
The bazaar pleased me.

414
00:51:21,190 --> 00:51:36,240
It was got up by the English residents, and their fancy-work was the fancy-work of the church bazaars in England, and I felt at home among it, and when my eyes rested on Rénee I saw the most delightful object I had seen for many weeks.

415
00:51:36,240 --> 00:51:46,810
I looked and longed, and longed and looked, and then suddenly in a moment one of the great good fortunes of my life happened to me.

416
00:51:46,810 --> 00:51:52,000
The beautiful doll was put up to be raffled, and my sister won her.

417
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:57,170
I trembled with joy as she and her wardrobe were put into my hands.

418
00:51:57,170 --> 00:51:58,650
I took her home.

419
00:51:58,650 --> 00:52:01,700
I dressed and undressed her twenty times a day.

420
00:52:01,700 --> 00:52:05,900
I made her play the part of heroine in all my favourite stories.

421
00:52:05,900 --> 00:52:11,810
I told her fairy-tales and took her to bed with me at night for company, but I never loved her.

422
00:52:11,810 --> 00:52:16,080
I have never been able to love a doll in my life.

423
00:52:17,600 --> 00:52:32,540
My mother came to me the next day as I was changing Rénee's wig, and said, "Don't you think it's almost time that you began to have some lessons again; I don't want my little girl to grow up quite ignorant, you wouldn't like that yourself, would you?"

424
00:52:32,540 --> 00:52:42,770
"I don't know," I said doubtfully, feeling that ignorance in a grown-up state was surely to be preferred to a return to Stamford and long division.

425
00:52:42,770 --> 00:52:50,600
"I am not going to send you to school," my mother hastened to add, doubtless seeing the cloud that gathered in my face.

426
00:52:50,600 --> 00:52:58,900
"I know a French lady here who has a little girl about your age, and she says that you can go and live with her for a little while and learn French."

427
00:52:58,900 --> 00:53:01,980
"Is she a nice little girl," I asked.

428
00:53:01,980 --> 00:53:03,670
"What is she like?"

429
00:53:03,670 --> 00:53:09,780
"Well, she's rather like your new doll," my mother laughed, "when it has the flaxen wig on.

430
00:53:09,780 --> 00:53:13,790
Think how nice it will be to write letters home in French."

431
00:53:13,790 --> 00:53:24,140
I knew Miss ——— could not write letters in French, and the prospect of crushing her with my new literary attainment filled my wicked little heart.

432
00:53:24,140 --> 00:53:31,980
"I should like to go and live with the little girl who is like my new dollie," I said, "if you will come and see me every day."

433
00:53:33,180 --> 00:53:37,530
So I went, my doll's clothes packed in their little tin trunk.

434
00:53:37,530 --> 00:53:48,680
And I stood stealing shy side-glances at Marguerite, who was certainly very like my doll, while my mother and her mother were exchanging last civilities.

435
00:53:48,680 --> 00:54:03,190
I was so pleased with the new surroundings, the very French interior, the excitement of being received as a member by a real French family, that I forgot to cry till the wheels of my mother's carriage had rolled away from the door.

436
00:54:03,190 --> 00:54:14,640
Then I was left, a little English child without a word of French in the bosom of a French family, and as this came upon me I burst into a flood of tears.

437
00:54:14,640 --> 00:54:22,570
Madame Lourdes could speak no English but she knew the universal language, the language of love and kindness.

438
00:54:22,570 --> 00:54:36,190
She drew me to her ample lap, wiped my eyes, smiled at me and chattered volubly in her own tongue words whose sense was dead to me, but whose tone breathed of tenderness and sympathy.

439
00:54:36,190 --> 00:54:38,150
By the time Mdlle.

440
00:54:38,150 --> 00:54:50,500
Lourdes, the only English-speaking member of the family came home from her daily round of teaching, Marguerite and I were unpacking my doll's clothes together and were laughing at our vain efforts to understand each other.

441
00:54:52,320 --> 00:54:54,800
I learned French in three mouths.

442
00:54:54,800 --> 00:55:00,470
All day I was with Madame Lourdes or Marguerite, neither of whom knew a word of English.

443
00:55:00,470 --> 00:55:06,580
It was French or silence, and any healthy child would have chosen French, as I did.

444
00:55:06,580 --> 00:55:09,070
They were three happy months.

445
00:55:09,070 --> 00:55:15,190
I adored Marguerite who was, I think, the typical good child of the French story-books.

446
00:55:15,190 --> 00:55:18,960
She wore her hair in a little yellow plait down her back.

447
00:55:18,960 --> 00:55:23,100
I do not think we ever got into wilful mischief.

448
00:55:23,100 --> 00:55:27,720
For instance, our starving the cat was quite unintentional.

449
00:55:27,720 --> 00:55:48,240
We were playing bandits in a sort of cellar that opened from the triangular courtyard in front of the house and it occurred to us that Mimi would make an excellent captive princess, so we caught her and put her in a hamper at the end of the cellar, and when my mother called to take us home to tea with her we rushed off and left the poor princess still a prisoner.

450
00:55:48,240 --> 00:56:12,520
If we hadn't been out that evening we must have been reminded of her existence by the search for her, but Madame Lourdes, failing to find the cat, concluded that she must have run away or met with an accident, and did not mention the matter to us out of consideration for our feelings, so that it was not till two nights later that I started up in bed about midnight and pulled Marguerite's yellow pigtail wildly.

451
00:56:12,520 --> 00:56:15,470
"Oh, Marguerite," I cried, "poor Mimi!"

452
00:56:15,470 --> 00:56:24,700
I had to pull at the pig-tail as though it was a bell-rope, and I had pulled three times before I could get Marguerite to understand what was the matter with me.

453
00:56:24,700 --> 00:56:28,530
Then she sat up in bed rigid with a great purpose.

454
00:56:28,530 --> 00:56:31,890
"We must go down and fetch her," she said.

455
00:56:31,890 --> 00:56:35,610
It was winter; the snow was on the ground.

456
00:56:35,610 --> 00:56:50,300
Marguerite thoughtfully put on her shoes and her dressing-gown, but I, with some vague recollection of bare-footed pilgrims, and some wild desire to make expiation for my crime, went down bare-footed, in my night-gown.

457
00:56:50,300 --> 00:56:56,590
The crime of forgetting a cat for three days was well paid for by that expedition.

458
00:56:56,590 --> 00:57:14,130
We crept through the house like little shivering mice across the courtyard, thinly sprinkled with snow, and into that awful black yawning cellar where nameless horrors lurked behind each bit of shapeless lumber, ready to leap out upon us as we passed.

459
00:57:14,130 --> 00:57:17,050
Marguerite did not share my terrors.

460
00:57:17,050 --> 00:57:21,280
She only remarked that it was very cold and that we must make haste.

461
00:57:21,280 --> 00:57:36,930
We opened the hamper fully expecting to find the captive dead, and my heart gave a leap of delight when, as we raised the lid, the large white Mimi crept out and began to rub herself against us with joyous purrings.

462
00:57:36,930 --> 00:57:43,320
I remember so well the feeling of her soft warm fur against my cold little legs.

463
00:57:43,320 --> 00:57:51,200
I caught the cat in my arms, and as I turned to go back to the house my half-frozen foot struck against something on the floor.

464
00:57:51,200 --> 00:57:54,350
It felt silky, I picked it up.

465
00:57:54,350 --> 00:57:56,000
It was Rénee.

466
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:00,130
She also had been a captive princess in our game of bandits.

467
00:58:00,130 --> 00:58:05,820
She also had been shut up here all this time, and I had never missed her!

468
00:58:05,820 --> 00:58:11,390
We took the cat and the doll back to bed with us and tried to get warm again.

469
00:58:11,390 --> 00:58:19,110
Marguerite was soon asleep, but I lay awake for a long time kissing and crying over the ill-used cat.

470
00:58:19,110 --> 00:58:22,120
I didn't get up again for a fortnight.

471
00:58:22,120 --> 00:58:29,430
My bare-footed pilgrimage cost me a frightful cold and the loss of several children's parties to which we had been invited.

472
00:58:29,430 --> 00:58:34,470
Marguerite, throughout my illness, behaved like an angel.

473
00:58:34,470 --> 00:58:41,030
I only remember one occasion on which I quarrelled with her—it was on the subject of dress.

474
00:58:41,030 --> 00:58:46,720
We were going to a children's party, and my best blue silk was put out for me to wear.

475
00:58:46,720 --> 00:58:54,870
"I wish you wouldn't near that," said Marguerite hesitatingly, "it makes my grey cashmere look so old."

476
00:58:54,870 --> 00:58:59,450
Now I had nothing else to wear but a brown frock which I hated.

477
00:58:59,450 --> 00:59:08,660
"Never mind," I said hypocritically, "it's better to be good than smart, everybody says so," and I put on my blue silk.

478
00:59:08,660 --> 00:59:17,810
When I was dressed, I pranced off to the kitchen to show my finery to the cook, and under her admiring eyes executed my best curtsey.

479
00:59:17,810 --> 00:59:26,120
It began, of course, by drawing the right foot back; it ended in a tub of clothes and water that was standing just behind me.

480
00:59:26,120 --> 00:59:45,770
I floundered out somehow, and my first thought was how funny I must have looked, and in another moment I should hove burst out laughing, but as I scrambled out, I saw Marguerite in the doorway smiling triumphantly, and heard her thin little voice say, "The blue silk can't mock the poor grey cashmere now!"

481
00:59:45,770 --> 00:59:49,450
An impulse of blind fury came upon me.

482
00:59:49,450 --> 00:59:58,910
I caught Marguerite by her little shoulders, and before the cook could interfere I had ducked her head-first into the tub of linen.

483
00:59:58,910 --> 01:00:11,710
Madame Lourdes behaved beautifully; she appeared on the scene at this moment, and, impartial as ever, she slapped us both, but when she heard from the cools the rights of the story, my sentence was "bed."

484
01:00:11,710 --> 01:00:16,100
"But Marguerite," said her mother, "has been punished enough for an unkind word."

485
01:00:16,100 --> 01:00:24,060
And Marguerite was indeed sobbing bitterly, while I was dry-eyed and still furious.

486
01:00:24,060 --> 01:00:28,540
"She can't go," I cried, "she hasn't got a dress!"

487
01:00:28,540 --> 01:00:35,960
"You have spoilt her dress," said Madame Lourdes coolly, "the least you can do is to lend her your brown one."

488
01:00:35,960 --> 01:00:46,470
And that excellent woman actually had the courage to send her own daughter to a party, in my dress, an exquisite punishment to us both.

489
01:00:46,470 --> 01:00:54,640
Marguerite came to my bedside that night; she had taken off the brown dress and wore her little flannel dressing-gown.

490
01:00:54,640 --> 01:00:57,230
" You're not cross now, are you?"

491
01:00:57,230 --> 01:00:58,210
she said.

492
01:00:58,210 --> 01:01:04,660
"I did beg mother to let you come, and I've not enjoyed myself a bit, and I've brought you this from the party."

493
01:01:04,660 --> 01:01:09,030
It was a beautiful little model of a coffeemill made in sugar.

494
01:01:09,030 --> 01:01:12,910
My resentment could not withstand this peace-offering.

495
01:01:12,910 --> 01:01:23,700
I never quarrelled with Marguerite again, and when my mother sent for me to join her at Bagneres I wept as bitterly at leaving Madame Lourdes as I had done at being left with her.

496
01:01:23,700 --> 01:01:30,830
"Cheer up my darling, my cabbage," said the dear woman as the tears stood in her own little grey eyes.

497
01:01:30,830 --> 01:01:36,080
"I have an instinct, a presentiment, which tells me we shall meet again."

498
01:01:36,080 --> 01:01:38,740
But we never have.

499
01:01:40,040 --> 01:01:42,180
End of Part 6

