PART 7
DISILLUSION

503
01:01:59,980 --> 01:02:03,160
I was sent with a servant from Pau to Bagnères.

504
01:02:03,160 --> 01:02:17,960
She soon dried my tears by reminding me of the hideous blue and white knitted cuffs which my hot and rebellious fingers had for weeks been busy in knitting for my mother, and which I should now be able to present personally.

505
01:02:17,960 --> 01:02:30,540
They were of a size suitable to the wrist of a man of about eight feet, and the irregularities at the edge where I had forgotten to slip the stitch were concealed by stiff little ruchings of blue satin ribbon.

506
01:02:30,540 --> 01:02:34,250
I thought of them with unspeakable pride.

507
01:02:34,250 --> 01:02:44,970
We reached Bagnères after dark, and my passion of joy at seeing my mother again was heightened by the knowledge that I had so rich a gift to bestow upon her.

508
01:02:44,970 --> 01:03:00,290
We had late dinner, in itself an event to me, and then I tasted for the first time the delicious chemin de fen, a kind of open tart made of almond paste and oranges covered with a crisp icing or caramel.

509
01:03:00,290 --> 01:03:10,600
I have never tasted this anywhere else, and though I have tried again and again to reproduce it in my own kitchen, I have never obtained even a measure of success.

510
01:03:10,600 --> 01:03:17,170
Even to this delicacy the thought of those blue and white cuffs added flavour.

511
01:03:17,170 --> 01:03:24,930
After dinner I slipped away and made hay of the contents of my box till I found the precious treasures.

512
01:03:24,930 --> 01:03:32,530
I returned solemnly to the room where my mother was sitting by the bright wood fire, with the wax candles on the polished table.

513
01:03:32,530 --> 01:03:42,410
"Mamma," I said (we called our mothers "mamma" in the sixties), "I have made you a present all my very own self, and it's in here."

514
01:03:42,410 --> 01:03:44,660
"Whatever can it be?"

515
01:03:44,660 --> 01:03:48,160
said my mother, affecting an earnest interest.

516
01:03:48,160 --> 01:03:50,920
She undid the paper slowly.

517
01:03:50,920 --> 01:03:53,470
"Oh, what beautiful cuffs!

518
01:03:53,470 --> 01:03:54,620
Thank you, dear.

519
01:03:54,620 --> 01:03:58,100
And did you make them all your very own self?"

520
01:03:59,280 --> 01:04:04,530
My sisters also looked at and praised the cuffs, and I went happy to bed.

521
01:04:04,530 --> 01:04:10,260
When I was lying between the sheets I heard one of my sisters laughing in the next room.

522
01:04:10,260 --> 01:04:14,770
She was talking, and I knew she was speaking of my precious cuffs.

523
01:04:14,770 --> 01:04:18,720
" They would just fit a coal-heaver" she said.

524
01:04:19,760 --> 01:04:26,840
She never knew that I heard her, but it was years before I forgave that unconscious outrage to my feelings.

525
01:04:28,040 --> 01:04:31,930
Bagnères de Bigorre is built in the midst of mountain streams.

526
01:04:31,930 --> 01:04:51,060
Streams cross the roads, streams run between the houses, under the houses, not quiet, placid little streams, such as meander through our English meadows, but violent, angry, rushing, boiling little mountain torrents that thunder along their rocky beds.

527
01:04:51,060 --> 01:04:57,880
Sometimes one of these streams is spanned by a dark arch, and a house built over it.

528
01:04:57,880 --> 01:05:07,370
What good fortune that one of these houses should have been the one selected by my mother—on quite other grounds, of course—and, oh!

529
01:05:07,370 --> 01:05:17,080
the double good fortune I, even I, was to sleep in the little bedroom actually built on the arch itself that spanned the mountain stream!

530
01:05:17,080 --> 01:05:22,370
It was delightful, it was romantic, it was fascinating.

531
01:05:22,370 --> 01:05:33,280
I could fancy myself a princess in a tower by the rushing Rhine as I heard the four-foot torrent go thundering along with a noise that would not have disgraced a full-grown river.

532
01:05:33,280 --> 01:05:41,050
It had every charm the imagination could desire, but it kept me awake till the small hours of the morning.

533
01:05:41,050 --> 01:05:58,600
It was humiliating to have to confess that even romance and a rushing torrent did not compensate for the loss of humdrum, commonplace sleep, but I accepted that humiliation and slept no more in the little room overhanging the torrent.

534
01:05:59,700 --> 01:06:11,640
The next day was, I confess, tiresome to me, and I in consequence tiresome to other people; the excitement of coming back to my mother had quickly worn off.

535
01:06:11,640 --> 01:06:15,940
My mother was busy letter-writing, so were my sisters.

536
01:06:15,940 --> 01:06:20,370
I missed Marguerite, Mimi, even my lessons.

537
01:06:20,370 --> 01:06:34,120
There was something terribly unhomelike about the polished floor, the polished wooden furniture, the marble-topped chest: of drawers with glass handles, and the cold greyness, of the stone-built houses outside.

538
01:06:34,120 --> 01:06:44,440
I wandered about the suite of apartments, every now and then rubbing myself like a kitten against my, mother's shoulder and murmuring, "I don't know what to do."

539
01:06:44,440 --> 01:06:49,580
I tried drawing, but the pencil was bad and the paper greasy.

540
01:06:49,580 --> 01:06:53,840
I thought of reading, but there was no book there I cared for.

541
01:06:53,840 --> 01:06:57,820
It was one of the longest days I ever spent.

542
01:06:57,820 --> 01:07:00,910
That evening my sister said to me—

543
01:07:00,910 --> 01:07:06,260
"Daisy, would you like to see a shepherdess, a real live shepherdess?"

544
01:07:07,620 --> 01:07:10,570
Now I had read of shepherdesses in my Contes de Fées.

545
01:07:10,570 --> 01:07:26,910
I knew that they wore rose-wreathed Watteau hats, short satin shirts, and flowered sills overdresses, that spinning was part of their daily toil, and that they danced in village festivals, generally at moments when the king's son was riding by to the hunt.

546
01:07:26,910 --> 01:07:30,310
"Oh, I should like to see a shepherdess," I said.

547
01:07:30,310 --> 01:07:35,720
"But do you mean a real one who keeps sheep and spins and everything?"

548
01:07:35,720 --> 01:07:46,640
"Oh, yes; she stands at her cottage door and spins while she watches her sheep, and eats a beautiful kind of yellow bread made of maize, that looks and tastes like cake.

549
01:07:46,640 --> 01:07:49,930
I daresay she would give you some if you asked her."

550
01:07:49,930 --> 01:07:53,400
The mention of the shepherdess dissipated my boredom.

551
01:07:53,400 --> 01:08:01,020
I climbed on my sister's knee and begged for a fairy story " And let it be about shepherdesses," I said.

552
01:08:01,020 --> 01:08:05,200
My sister had a genius for telling fairystories.

553
01:08:05,200 --> 01:08:14,330
If she would only write them now as she told them then, all the children in England would insist on having her fairy-stories, and none others.

554
01:08:14,330 --> 01:08:26,190
She told me a story that had a shepherdess in it and a king's son, of course; a wicked fairy, a dragon and a coach and many other interesting and delightful characters.

555
01:08:26,190 --> 01:08:39,660
I went to bed happy in the knowledge that the fairy-world was stooping to earth, and that the fairy-world and this world of ours would touch to-morrow, and touch at the point where I should behold the shepherdess.

556
01:08:41,060 --> 01:08:48,870
I spent the next morning happily enough in drawing fancy portraits of the shepherdess, the king's son, and the wicked fairy.

557
01:08:48,870 --> 01:08:57,840
My sister lent me her paint, and her best sable brush, and life blossomed anew under the influence of a good night's rest.

558
01:08:57,840 --> 01:09:01,690
In the afternoon we started out to see the shepherdess.

559
01:09:01,690 --> 01:09:12,150
Over the cobble stones of the streets, among the little mountain torrents, we picked our way, and came at last to green pastures at the foot of the mountains.

560
01:09:12,150 --> 01:09:19,640
The Pyrenees were so bright in their snow coats touched by the sun that our eyes could not bear to look at them.

561
01:09:19,640 --> 01:09:24,250
"We shall soon come to the shepherdess," said my sister, cheerfully.

562
01:09:24,250 --> 01:09:28,370
"You must not expect her to be like the ones in fairy-tales, you know."

563
01:09:28,370 --> 01:09:34,350
"Of course not," said I; but in my heart I did.

564
01:09:34,350 --> 01:09:40,310
We came presently to a sloping pasture, strewn with fragments of rock.

565
01:09:40,310 --> 01:09:46,930
"There she is," said my sister, "sitting on a stone spinning with her sheep round her."

566
01:09:46,930 --> 01:09:52,930
I looked; but could see no one save one old woman, the witch probably.

567
01:09:52,930 --> 01:09:54,240
"Where?

568
01:09:54,240 --> 01:09:56,910
I don't see her," I said.

569
01:09:56,910 --> 01:10:00,680
By, this time we were close to the old woman.

570
01:10:00,680 --> 01:10:08,900
"There's your shepherdess," said my sister in English, "look at her nice quaint dress and the spindle and distaff.

571
01:10:10,240 --> 01:10:13,950
I looked, but such a sight had no charms for me.

572
01:10:13,950 --> 01:10:17,480
Where was my flowered-silk, Watteau-hatted maiden?

573
01:10:17,480 --> 01:10:20,230
Where was her crook with the pink ribbons on it ?

574
01:10:20,230 --> 01:10:25,370
And as for the king's son, his horse could never have ridden up this steep hillside.

575
01:10:25,370 --> 01:10:40,590
It was a disenchanted world where I stood gazing sadly, at a wrinkled faced old woman in a blue woollen petticoat and coarse linen apron, a gay-coloured shawl crossed on her breast, a gay-coloured handkerchief knotted round her head.

576
01:10:40,590 --> 01:10:49,670
She had wooden shoes, and her crook was a common wooden one with a bit of iron at the end, and not a ribbon nor a flower on it.

577
01:10:49,670 --> 01:10:52,030
But she was very kind.

578
01:10:52,030 --> 01:10:59,080
She took us up to her little hut among the rocks and gave us milk and maize bread at my sister's request.

579
01:10:59,080 --> 01:11:11,030
The maize bread was like sawdust, or a Bath bun of the week before last; but had it been ambrosia, I could not have tasted a second mouthful—my heart was too full.

580
01:11:11,030 --> 01:11:14,070
I came home in silence.

581
01:11:14,070 --> 01:11:18,240
My sister was sad because the little treat had not pleased me.

582
01:11:18,240 --> 01:11:25,640
I did not mean to be ungrateful; I was only struggling savagely with the misery of my first disillusion.

583
01:11:25,640 --> 01:11:32,800
Like Mrs. Over-the-way, I had looked for pink roses, and found only feuilles mortes.

584
01:11:34,280 --> 01:11:36,340
End of Part 7

