587
01:11:49,260 --> 01:11:52,830
PART 8
IN AUVERGNE

588
01:11:52,830 --> 01:11:55,680
We were to leave Bagnères.

589
01:11:55,680 --> 01:12:02,360
Imagine my delight when I found we were to travel not by train, but in an open carriage.

590
01:12:02,360 --> 01:12:15,860
In this we were to drive through the mountains, the mysterious snow-clad mountains, into Spain, where the Alhambra was, and oranges and Spanish nuts, and all sorts of delightful things.

591
01:12:15,860 --> 01:12:18,270
But alas for my hopes!

592
01:12:18,270 --> 01:12:28,290
My brother at home in England chose to have whooping-cough, and so our horses' heads were turned north, and farewell for ever to my visions of Spain.

593
01:12:28,290 --> 01:12:33,860
We drove through lovely country to the other Bagnères, Bagnères de Luchon.

594
01:12:33,860 --> 01:12:38,200
On the way we passed a large yellow-stone castle on a hill.

595
01:12:38,200 --> 01:12:50,970
Most of the castle was in ruins, but a great square tower, without door or window, still stood as strong and firm as on the day when the last stone was patted into place with the trowel.

596
01:12:50,970 --> 01:12:55,700
We wandered round this tower in vain, trying to find a door.

597
01:12:55,700 --> 01:13:12,850
" But it is that there is no door." said our driver at last; "within that tower is buried a treasure; some day a great wind will blow, and then that tower will fall to the ground, and then the folks of the village will divide the treasure, and become kings of France.

598
01:13:12,850 --> 01:13:15,150
It is an old prophecy."

599
01:13:15,150 --> 01:13:21,990
"But," suggested my mother, "has no one tried to get in and see if there really is a treasure?"

600
01:13:21,990 --> 01:13:24,690
The driver crossed himself.

601
01:13:24,690 --> 01:13:26,320
"The saints forbid!"

602
01:13:26,320 --> 01:13:30,270
be said; "who are we that we should interfere with the holy prophecy?

603
01:13:30,270 --> 01:13:33,710
Besides, the tower is haunted."

604
01:13:33,710 --> 01:13:42,120
We could not help wondering how far the ghost and prophecy would have protected that tower from English village boys.

605
01:13:42,120 --> 01:13:48,120
We drove on; presently we stopped at a little wayside shrine, with a painted image of St.

606
01:13:48,120 --> 01:13:51,460
John in it, and a little shell of holy water.

607
01:13:51,460 --> 01:13:55,760
At the side of that shrine was a stone with an iron ring in it.

608
01:13:55,760 --> 01:14:04,590
Nothing more was needed to convince me that this was the entrance to a subterranean passage, leading to the tower where the treasure was.

609
01:14:04,590 --> 01:14:08,390
Imagine the dreams that occupied me for the rest of the drive!

610
01:14:08,390 --> 01:14:30,870
If I could creep back at the dead of night to the shrine—a thing which as a matter of fact I would much rather have died than have attempted—if I should pull up that heavy stone and go down the damp subterranean passage and find the treasure in iron boxes—rubies and diamonds and emeralds, and beautiful gold and silver dishes!

611
01:14:30,870 --> 01:15:03,860
Then we should all be very rich for the rest of our lives, and I could send Marguerite a talking doll, that opened and shut its eyes, and a pony-carriage, and each of the boys should have a new paint-box, with real moist colours and as many sable brushes as they liked—twenty each if they wanted them, and I should have a chariot drawn by four tame zebras in red and silver harness, and my mother should have a gold crown, with diamonds, for Sundays, and a silver one, with rubies and emeralds, for every day, and—

612
01:15:03,860 --> 01:15:12,330
I imagine I fell asleep at this point, and awoke to find myself lifted out of the carriage at Bagnères de Luchon.

613
01:15:12,330 --> 01:15:27,740
I didn't go back and lift up the stone with the iron ring, but the dream was a serviceable one, and did duty nobly in idle hours for many a long year; in fact, I come across it unexpectedly sometimes even now.

614
01:15:29,140 --> 01:15:34,220
We spent a day or two at Bagnères de Lnchon, and I believe it rained all the time.

615
01:15:34,220 --> 01:15:40,580
We drove in a drizzling rain across a rather gloomy country, to see the Cascade d'Enfer.

616
01:15:40,580 --> 01:15:49,280
As my memory serves me, we crossed a dreary plain and entered a sort of theatre, or semi-circle of high black rocks.

617
01:15:49,280 --> 01:15:56,430
In the centre of the horse-shoe, down the face of the rock, ran a thin silver line.

618
01:15:56,430 --> 01:16:23,030
This was the Cascade d'Enfer, eminently unimpressive on first view, but when we got out of our carriage and walked across the rough ground, and stood under the heavy shadow of the black cliffs, the thin white line had changed, and grown to a dense body of smoothly-falling water that fell over the cliff's sheer edge, and disappeared like a column of green glass into a circular hole at the foot of the cliff.

619
01:16:23,030 --> 01:16:31,990
"That hole goes down, down," said our guide, "no one knows how far, except the good God who made it."

620
01:16:31,990 --> 01:16:40,740
The water did not fill up the hole, an empty black space, some yards wide, was between us and the falling water.

621
01:16:40,740 --> 01:16:44,590
Our guide heaved a lump of rock over the edge.

622
01:16:44,590 --> 01:16:53,100
"You not hear it strike water," he said, and though we listened for some time, we did not hear it strike anything.

623
01:16:53,100 --> 01:16:55,800
That was the horror of it.

624
01:16:57,220 --> 01:16:59,340
We drove on the next day to St.

625
01:16:59,340 --> 01:17:10,290
Bertrand de Comminges, a little town on a hill with many steeples, whose bells answered each other with sweet jangling voices as we reached its gates in the peace of the evening.

626
01:17:10,290 --> 01:17:18,310
Most of this driving-tour has faded from my mind, but I shall never forget the drive from Aurillac to Murat.

627
01:17:18,310 --> 01:17:24,520
We started late in the afternoon, because my sisters wished to see the Auvergnes mountains by moonlight.

628
01:17:24,520 --> 01:17:31,510
We had a large open carriage, with a sort of rumble behind and a wide box-seat in front.

629
01:17:31,510 --> 01:17:41,290
The driver, a blue-bloused ruffian of plausible manners, agreed to take us and our luggage to Murat for a certain price, which I have forgotten.

630
01:17:41,290 --> 01:17:47,750
All our luggage was packed upon his carriage; we, too were packed in it, and we started.

631
01:17:47,750 --> 01:17:53,720
About five miles from the town the driver halted, and came to the door of the carriage.

632
01:17:53,720 --> 01:18:00,780
"Mesdames," be said "a young relative of mine will join us here, he will sit on the box with me."

633
01:18:00,780 --> 01:18:08,500
My mother objected, that as we were paying for the carriage, we had a right to refuse to allow his friend to enter it.

634
01:18:08,500 --> 01:18:21,430
"As you will, madame," he said calmly, "but if you refuse to accommodate my stepson, a young man of the most high distinction, I shall place you and your boxes in the middle of the road, and leave you planted there."

635
01:18:21,430 --> 01:18:30,480
Three English ladies and a little girl alone in a strange country, five miles from any town, what could we do?

636
01:18:30,480 --> 01:18:33,670
My mother consented.

637
01:18:33,670 --> 01:18:39,390
A mile or two further on two blue-bloused figures got up suddenly from their seat by the roadside.

638
01:18:39,390 --> 01:18:43,510
"My father and brother-in-law," said our driver.

639
01:18:43,510 --> 01:18:51,170
My mother saw that protest was vain, so these two were stowed in the rumble, and the carriage jolted on more heavily.

640
01:18:51,170 --> 01:18:54,340
We now began to be seriously frightened.

641
01:18:54,340 --> 01:18:57,300
I know I endured agonies of torture.

642
01:18:57,300 --> 01:19:04,300
No doubt these were highwaymen, and at the nearest convenient spot they would stop the carriage and murder us all.

643
01:19:04,300 --> 01:19:10,760
In the next few miles two more passengers were added to our number, a cousin and an uncle.

644
01:19:10,760 --> 01:19:15,490
All wore blue blouses, and had villainous-looking faces.

645
01:19:15,490 --> 01:19:26,730
The uncle, who looked like a porpoise and smelt horribly of brandy, was put inside the carriage with us, because there was now no room left in any other part of the conveyance.

646
01:19:26,730 --> 01:19:32,740
The family party laughed and jolted in a patois wholly unintelligible to us.

647
01:19:32,740 --> 01:19:39,660
I was convinced that they were arranging for the disposal of our property and our bodies after the murder.

648
01:19:39,660 --> 01:19:44,970
My mother and sisters were talking in low voices in English.

649
01:19:44,970 --> 01:19:58,620
"If we only get to the half-way house safe," she said, " we can appeal to the landlord for protection," and after a seemingly interminable drive we got to the half-way house.

650
01:19:58,620 --> 01:20:12,890
It was a low, roughly-built, dirty auberge, with an uneven, earthen floor, the ceiling, benches and tables black with age, just the place where travellers are always murdered in Christmas stories.

651
01:20:12,890 --> 01:20:19,310
My teeth chattered with terror, but there was a certain pleasure in the excitement all the same.

652
01:20:19,310 --> 01:20:31,850
We ordered supper; it was now near midnight, and while it was being prepared, my mother emptied her purse of all, save the money promised to the driver, and a ten-france piece to pay for our suppers.

653
01:20:31,850 --> 01:20:39,190
The rest of the money she put into a canvas bag which hung round her neck, where she always carried her bank-notes.

654
01:20:39,190 --> 01:20:42,050
The supper was like something out of a fairy tale.

655
01:20:42,050 --> 01:20:51,250
A clean cloth, in itself an incongruous accident in such a place, new milk, new bread, and new honey.

656
01:20:51,250 --> 01:20:59,040
When the woman brought in our bill, my mother poured out her woes, and confessed her fear of the driver's intention.

657
01:20:59,040 --> 01:21:05,040
"Nonsense," said the woman briskly, " he's the best man in the world—he's my own son!

658
01:21:05,040 --> 01:21:09,740
Surely he has a right to give his own relations a lift in his carriage if he likes!"

659
01:21:09,740 --> 01:21:16,020
"But we had paid for his carriage, he has no right to put other people in when we are paying for it!"

660
01:21:16,020 --> 01:21:18,030
"Oh, yes, he has!"

661
01:21:18,030 --> 01:21:19,950
retorted the woman shortly.

662
01:21:19,950 --> 01:21:34,120
"You paid him so much to take you to Murat, and he will take you to Murat; but there was nothing said about his not taking anyone else, and he says now he won't take you on to Murat unless you pay him double the fare you agreed for, his horses are tired!"

663
01:21:34,120 --> 01:21:41,400
"I should think they were," muttered my sister, "considering the number of extra passengers they have dragged."

664
01:21:42,800 --> 01:21:45,340
My mother emptied her purse on the table.

665
01:21:45,340 --> 01:21:57,290
"You see," she said, "here is only the money I promised your son and enough to pay for our suppers; but when we get to Murat I shall find money waiting for me, and I will give him what you ask."

666
01:21:57,290 --> 01:22:03,520
I believe this conduct of my mother saved us at any rate from being robbed by violence.

667
01:22:03,520 --> 01:22:09,660
The inn stood quite by itself in one of the loneliest spots in the mountains of Auvergnes.

668
01:22:09,660 --> 01:22:15,920
If they had believed that we were worth robbing, and had chosen to rob us, nothing could have saved us.

669
01:22:16,940 --> 01:22:18,200
We started again.

670
01:22:18,200 --> 01:22:28,430
My mother now began to make light of the adventure, and my terror subsided sufficiently for me to be able to note the terrible grandeur of the scenery we passed through.

671
01:22:28,430 --> 01:22:56,190
Vast masses of bare volcanic rock, iron grey in the moonlight, with black chasms and mysterious gorges, each one eloquent of bandits and gnomes, and an absolute stillness, save for the rattle of our carriage, as though, with vegetation, life too had ceased, as though indeed we rode through a land deathstill, under the enchantment of some evil magician.

672
01:22:56,190 --> 01:23:03,360
The rocks and the mountains beyond them towered higher and higher on each side of the road.

673
01:23:03,360 --> 01:23:16,150
The strip of flat ground between us and the rocks grew narrower, till presently the road wound between two vast black cliffs, and the strip of sky high up looked bright and blue.

674
01:23:16,150 --> 01:23:25,420
The tall cliffs were on either side, and presently I saw with dismay that in front of us the dark cliff stretched right across the road.

675
01:23:25,420 --> 01:23:29,460
We seemed to be driving straight into the heart of the rock.

676
01:23:29,460 --> 01:23:44,440
In another moment, with a crack of the whip and an encouraging word or two, the driver urged his horses to a gallop, and we plunged through a dark archway into pitch darkness, for, with a jolt, the carriage lamps went out.

677
01:23:44,440 --> 01:23:51,740
We had just been able to see that we had passed out of the night air into a tunnel cut in the solid rock.

678
01:23:51,740 --> 01:24:00,340
Oh, how thankful we were then that the porpoise and all the rest of our driver's relations had been left behind at the half-way house.

679
01:24:01,460 --> 01:24:04,620
The driver lighted the lamps again almost immediately.

680
01:24:04,620 --> 01:24:20,310
He seemed in a better temper than before, and explained to us that this was the great arch under the mountains, and to me he added: "It will be something for you to remember and to tell your children about when you are old," which was certainly true.

681
01:24:20,310 --> 01:24:23,490
That tunnel was unbearably long.

682
01:24:23,490 --> 01:24:34,110
As we rattled through its cavernous depths, I could not persuade myself that at any moment our driver's accomplices might not spring out upon us and kill us there and then.

683
01:24:34,110 --> 01:24:35,790
Who would ever have known?

684
01:24:35,790 --> 01:24:40,680
Oh, the relief of seeing at last a faint pin-prick of light!

685
01:24:40,680 --> 01:24:49,970
It grew larger and larger and larger, and at last, through another arch, we rattled out into the moonlight again.

686
01:24:49,970 --> 01:24:55,870
Of course, I shall never know now how many of the terrors of that night were imaginary.

687
01:24:55,870 --> 01:25:01,170
It is not pleasant, even now, to think of what might have happened.

688
01:25:01,170 --> 01:25:11,960
At last we reached our journey's end, a miserable, filthy inn, and, with a thankful heart, saw the last of our blue-bloused driver.

689
01:25:13,040 --> 01:25:22,360
The landlady objected very strongly to letting us in, and we objected still more strongly to the accommodation which she at last consented to offer us.

690
01:25:22,360 --> 01:25:28,680
The sheets were grey with dirt, and the pillows grimed with the long succession of heads that had lain on them.

691
01:25:28,680 --> 01:25:32,390
A fire was the only good thing that we got at Murat.

692
01:25:32,390 --> 01:25:34,650
To go to bed was impossible.

693
01:25:34,650 --> 01:25:40,020
We sat round the fire waiting for daylight and the first morning train.

694
01:25:40,020 --> 01:25:42,580
My mother took me on her knee.

695
01:25:42,580 --> 01:25:47,160
I grew warm and very comfortable and forgot all my troubles.

696
01:25:47,160 --> 01:25:54,690
"Ah," I said, with sleepy satisfaction "this is very nice; it's just like home."

697
01:25:54,690 --> 01:26:06,940
The contrast between my words and that filthy, squalid inn must have been irresistibly comic, for my mother and sisters laughed till I thought they would never stop.

698
01:26:06,940 --> 01:26:32,280
My innocent remark and some bread and milk—the only things clean enough to touch—cheered us all up wonderfully, and in another twenty-four hours my mother and sisters were all saying to each other that perhaps, after all, there had been nothing to be frightened about; but all the same, I don't think any of that party would ever have cared to face another night drive through the mountains of Auvergne.

699
01:26:32,280 --> 01:26:37,120
End of Part 8

