702
01:26:49,720 --> 01:26:53,280
PART 9
LA HAYE

703
01:26:54,540 --> 01:27:02,470
After our experience in Auvergnes, the rest of our travel was so flat as to have faded almost entirely from my memory.

704
01:27:02,470 --> 01:27:09,590
As soon as we reached England, I was sent to school—to a school of which I shall have more to say presently.

705
01:27:09,590 --> 01:27:12,120
There were only twenty girls.

706
01:27:12,120 --> 01:27:21,150
Mrs. MacBean was one of the best and kindest women who ever lived—a devoted Christian with a heart large enough to take in all her girls.

707
01:27:21,150 --> 01:27:25,170
If I could have been happy at any school I should have been happy there.

708
01:27:25,170 --> 01:27:33,700
And I was not actively unhappy, for I lived on my mother's promise that in July I should go back to her again.

709
01:27:33,700 --> 01:27:39,270
Where she was I didn't know; but I knew she was looking for a pretty home for us all.

710
01:27:39,270 --> 01:27:41,560
I used to write letters to her addressed to St.

711
01:27:41,560 --> 01:27:45,680
Martin's le Grand, which I think I believed to be in Paris.

712
01:27:45,680 --> 01:27:55,340
At last the news came that she had decided to live at Dinan in Brittany, and that in two short days I was to go by boat and join her.

713
01:27:55,340 --> 01:27:57,470
One day passed.

714
01:27:57,470 --> 01:28:02,080
The next day at dinner I was hugging myself on the thought of the morrow.

715
01:28:02,080 --> 01:28:07,940
"To-morrow," I said to the girl next to me, "I shall be going to my mother in France."

716
01:28:07,940 --> 01:28:09,750
"Oh, no, dear!"

717
01:28:09,750 --> 01:28:12,120
said the governess at the foot of the table.

718
01:28:12,120 --> 01:28:15,650
"Miss MacBean says you're not going till Wednesday."

719
01:28:15,650 --> 01:28:20,810
With a crash my card-castle came tumbling about my ears.

720
01:28:20,810 --> 01:28:25,610
Wednesday might as well have been next year—it seemed so far off.

721
01:28:25,610 --> 01:28:32,910
I burst into passionate weeping just as the servant placed a large plate of steaming black-currant pudding before me.

722
01:28:32,910 --> 01:28:39,440
I saw through my tears how vexed Miss MacBean looked; she hadn't meant to break the news to me in this way.

723
01:28:39,440 --> 01:28:43,980
"Come, Daisy," she said after a while "Don't cry, dear.

724
01:28:43,980 --> 01:28:47,660
Have some black-currant pudding—nice black-currant pudding."

725
01:28:47,660 --> 01:28:50,540
"I don't want any black-currant pudding!"

726
01:28:50,540 --> 01:28:51,450
I cried.

727
01:28:51,450 --> 01:28:52,480
"I hate it!

728
01:28:52,480 --> 01:28:54,780
I never want any pudding again!"

729
01:28:54,780 --> 01:29:02,870
And, with that, I rushed from the room; and from that day to this I have never been able to tolerate black-currant pudding.

730
01:29:02,870 --> 01:29:09,850
Every one was very kind to me; but there was not any one there who could at all understand the agony that that delay cost me.

731
01:29:09,850 --> 01:29:15,200
I didn't care to eat, I didn't care to sleep or play or read.

732
01:29:15,200 --> 01:29:17,350
When my mother met me at St.

733
01:29:17,350 --> 01:29:24,610
Malo on the following Thursday, her first words were, "Why, how pale and ill the child looks!"

734
01:29:24,610 --> 01:29:29,330
My sister suggested that it was the steamboat; but I don't believe it was.

735
01:29:29,330 --> 01:29:34,120
I believe it was the awful shock that came to me over the black-currant pudding.

736
01:29:35,680 --> 01:29:49,510
A long drive on a diligence by miles and miles of straight white road—the fatigue of the journey forgotten in the consciousness that I was going home, not to an hotel, not to a boarding-house, but home.

737
01:29:49,510 --> 01:29:57,530
The small material objects that surround one's daily life have always influenced me deeply.

738
01:29:57,530 --> 01:30:09,610
Even as a child I found that in a familiar entourage one could be contented, if not happy; but hotels and boarding-houses and lodgings have always bored me to extinction.

739
01:30:09,610 --> 01:30:23,460
Of course, as a matter of theory, one ought to carry one's intellectual atmosphere with one and be independent of surroundings; but, as a matter of practice, it can't be done, at least, by me.

740
01:30:23,460 --> 01:30:29,890
I have a cat-like fondness for things I am accustomed to, and I am not singular in this respect.

741
01:30:29,890 --> 01:30:40,930
I once knew a woman who, after years of genteel poverty and comfortless economy, had an opportunity of a new life in comparatively affluent circumstances.

742
01:30:40,930 --> 01:30:43,360
"Why ever don't you accept it?"

743
01:30:43,360 --> 01:30:46,060
I said when she told me of it.

744
01:30:46,060 --> 01:30:49,430
"I can't make up my mind to it," she said.

745
01:30:49,430 --> 01:30:52,540
"You see, I should have to leave the furniture."

746
01:30:53,980 --> 01:31:01,420
I felt some sympathy for her, though I hope that in her place I should have been strong-minded enough to make another choice.

747
01:31:02,600 --> 01:31:09,470
At last the diligence drew up at crossroads, where a cart was waiting, and to this our luggage was transferred.

748
01:31:09,470 --> 01:31:13,570
It turned up one of the side roads, and we followed on foot.

749
01:31:13,570 --> 01:31:22,960
Up a hill wound the road, a steep wooded slope on one side, and on the other a high, clay bank set with dainty ferns.

750
01:31:22,960 --> 01:31:29,740
Here and there a tiny spring trickled down to join the little stream that ran beside the road.

751
01:31:29,740 --> 01:31:39,700
We turned a corner by a farm, through a herd of gaunt pigs nearly as big as donkeys—the sight of which made me clasp my mother's hand more tightly.

752
01:31:39,700 --> 01:31:49,140
Each pig had a bar of wood suspended from his neck by a string, so that if he tried to stray through the hedge, the bar would catch and hold him back.

753
01:31:49,140 --> 01:31:53,730
All the pigs tried to walk over this bar as it hung against their forelegs.

754
01:31:53,730 --> 01:31:59,710
They never succeeded; but the action gave them all the air of high-stepping carriage-horses.

755
01:31:59,710 --> 01:32:05,930
Then we walked a little further along the white road, and the cart turned in at a wooden gate.

756
01:32:05,930 --> 01:32:15,520
We followed along the carriage-drive which ran along outside the high red wall of the big garden, then through a plantation of huge horse-chestnut trees.

757
01:32:15,520 --> 01:32:22,300
To the left, I could see ricks, cows and pigs, all the bustle and colour of a farm-yard.

758
01:32:23,340 --> 01:32:32,580
Two great brown gates swung back on their hinges and we passed through them into the courtyard of the dearest home of my childhood.

759
01:32:32,580 --> 01:32:35,090
The courtyard was square.

760
01:32:35,090 --> 01:32:51,020
One side was formed by the house; dairy, coach-house and the chicken-house formed the second side; on the third were stable, cow-house and goat-shed; on the fourth wood-shed, dogkennel, and the great gates by which we had entered.

761
01:32:51,020 --> 01:33:01,050
The house itself was an ordinary white-washed, slate-roofed, French country house, with an immense walled fruit garden on the other side of it.

762
01:33:01,050 --> 01:33:05,600
There never was such another garden, there never will be!

763
01:33:05,600 --> 01:33:17,660
Peaches, apricots, nectarines, and grapes of all kinds, lined the inside walls; the avenue that ran down the middle of it was of fig trees and standard peach-trees.

764
01:33:17,660 --> 01:33:27,160
There were raspberries, cherries and strawberries, and flowers mingling with fruits and vegetables in a confusion the most charming in the world.

765
01:33:27,160 --> 01:33:38,420
Along the end of the garden was a great arcade of black, clipped yews, so thick and strong that a child could crawl on the outside of it without falling through.

766
01:33:38,420 --> 01:33:45,690
Above the dairy and coach-house was an immense hay-loft, a straw-loft over the stable and cow-house.

767
01:33:45,690 --> 01:33:48,900
What play-rooms for wet days!

768
01:33:48,900 --> 01:33:57,490
Beyond the chicken-house was the orchard, full of twisted grey apple trees, beneath whose boughs in due season the barley grew.

769
01:33:57,490 --> 01:34:04,590
Beyond, a network of lanes, fringed with maiden-hair, led away into fairyland.

770
01:34:04,590 --> 01:34:09,980
My brothers eagerly led me round to show me all the treasures of the new home.

771
01:34:09,980 --> 01:34:14,950
There was a swing in the orchard, there were trees full of cherries, white and black.

772
01:34:14,950 --> 01:34:18,760
"And we may eat as many as we like," said Alfred.

773
01:34:18,760 --> 01:34:27,600
That afternoon we gathered a waste-paper basket full of cherries, and, with strenuous greed, set ourselves to empty it.

774
01:34:27,600 --> 01:34:35,050
We didn't succeed, of course; but the effort, so far as I remember, was attended by no evil consequences.

775
01:34:35,050 --> 01:34:41,720
We gave what we couldn't eat to the little black English pig, another of the treasures of the new home.

776
01:34:41,720 --> 01:34:48,860
There was a little black cow, there was a goat who resented with her horns my efforts after goat's milk.

777
01:34:48,860 --> 01:34:54,200
I learnt to milk her afterwards though, and she grew very kind and condescending.

778
01:34:54,200 --> 01:35:01,870
Then there were two ponies, Punch and Judy, and Punch, my brothers told me proudly, was for us to ride.

779
01:35:01,870 --> 01:35:07,050
This was the crowning happiness; we had never had a pony of our own before.

780
01:35:07,050 --> 01:35:12,400
He was a tiresome, pigheaded little beast that pony; but we loved him dearly.

781
01:35:12,400 --> 01:35:27,510
He had a way of pretending to be frightfully thirsty when you were out riding him, and when, in the kindness of your heart, you let him bend his head to a wayside pond for a drink, be would kick up his wicked little heels and over his head you had to go.

782
01:35:27,510 --> 01:35:34,350
If he could rub you off against a tree as you rode across the fields, he would do it with all the pleasure in life.

783
01:35:34,350 --> 01:35:51,050
He was rather good at jumping, and he and I had some pleasant cross-country expeditions; but if anything in the nature of the obstacle you put him at happened to strike his fancy disagreeably, he had a clever way of stopping short at the last moment, when, of course, you went over his head.

784
01:35:51,050 --> 01:35:57,140
He threw me three times in this way in one morning; but after that I was up to him.

785
01:35:58,880 --> 01:36:00,880
End of Part 9

