788
01:36:13,280 --> 01:36:18,080
PART 10
PIRATES AND EXPLORERS

789
01:36:19,480 --> 01:36:22,490
That summer was an ideally happy one.

790
01:36:22,490 --> 01:36:35,810
My mother, with a wisdom for which I shall thank her all my days, allowed us to run wild; we were expected to appear at meals with some approach to punctuality, and with hands and faces moderately clean.

791
01:36:35,810 --> 01:37:04,320
Sometimes when visitors were expected, we were seized and scrubbed, and clothed, and made to look something like the good little children we were not; then my brothers fidgeted awkwardly on their chairs and tried to conceal their hands and feet, while I nibbled a biscuit or cake in an agony of shyness, not quite unrelieved by a sneaking appreciation of my fine dress, an appreciation for which my brothers would never have forgiven me, had I been foolish enough to show it.

792
01:37:04,320 --> 01:37:11,080
But, as a rule, we were left to go our own way, and a very happy way it was.

793
01:37:11,080 --> 01:37:20,310
I don't mean that we were neglected; my eldest sister was always a refuge on wet days when a fairy story seemed to be the best thing to be had.

794
01:37:20,310 --> 01:37:35,300
In the midst of all the parties, picnics and gaieties in which our elders were plunged, my other sister found time to read aloud to us, and to receive such confidences as we deemed it wise to make concerning our plans and our plays.

795
01:37:36,300 --> 01:37:39,620
We had gauged the possibilities of the lofts correctly.

796
01:37:39,620 --> 01:37:44,600
With trusses of hay or straw, a magnificent fort could be made.

797
01:37:44,600 --> 01:37:56,950
I usually held the fort when the boys had built it, and the weakness of the garrison was lessened by the introduction of the two dogs, who defended it with me nobly, understanding perfectly the parts they had to play.

798
01:37:56,950 --> 01:38:00,040
We got the black pig up once, but that was a failure.

799
01:38:00,040 --> 01:38:41,160
When there was no time to organise a play, when it was not worth while to begin anything because dinner or breakfast would be ready in a few minutes, it was a constant delight to scale the wall behind the stable, and watch the great wooden wheel slowly dragged round the circular stone trough where the apples for cider lay; the old, blind, white horse harnessed to the wheel went sleepily round and round; you could hear the crunch, crunch of the apples as the great wooden wheel went over them, and smell the sweet scent of the crushed fruit as you sat swinging your legs on the wall among the yellow stone-crop and sulphur-coloured snap-dragon;

800
01:38:41,160 --> 01:39:07,500
or if you had the time to spare, what rapture to balance yourself on the edge of the stone trough, and wall: round it just behind the big wheel, knowing that if you slipped, you might fall on the muddy track outside, but that you were much more likely to fall into the trough itself, in which case your pinafore and stockings (we wore white stockings then) would be richly stained with apple juice to the colour of red rust.

801
01:39:07,500 --> 01:39:18,880
If the farmer were in a good temper, he would sometimes take you in to see the apples put in the press; you had to climb up by rough steps cut in the beams if the press was nearly full.

802
01:39:18,880 --> 01:39:29,730
At the top, on a little platform, stood the farmer, drawing up the crushed apples from below by bucketsful, and spreading them on their bed of clean straw with a wooden shovel.

803
01:39:29,730 --> 01:39:43,130
A layer of straw and a layer of apples, and when the press was full, the big beams screwed down, we hastened below to see the russet juice run out from its stone channel into the great vats.

804
01:39:43,130 --> 01:40:07,840
Though the farm adjoined our house, it was not our property, but as far as we children were concerned, it was just as good as ours, for the farmer allowed us the same privileges that he accorded to his own children; that is to say, if the farmer were in a good temper, we might watch any of the farming operations, if he was not, his own children had to keep out of the way, and so had we.

805
01:40:08,980 --> 01:40:12,690
There was a delightful pond in the field where the farm horses went to drink.

806
01:40:12,690 --> 01:40:18,700
It had a trampled muddy shore on one side, and on the other a high bank of yellow clay.

807
01:40:18,700 --> 01:40:26,430
We made a raft, of course, out of an old door and two barrels, and successfully sailed across to the yellow cliffs.

808
01:40:26,430 --> 01:40:35,350
"How nice it would be," I said, "if there were a cave in these cliffs; we could have no end of a good time and be pirates and things!"

809
01:40:35,350 --> 01:40:45,220
"You don't suppose," said Alfred scornfully, "that a pirate chief would wait to find a cave if he wanted one—he would make one of course; I shall make one."

810
01:40:45,220 --> 01:40:49,560
"I don't believe you can," said Harry and I in a breath.

811
01:40:49,560 --> 01:40:53,400
"All right," said my brother, "you'll see!"

812
01:40:53,400 --> 01:41:02,440
Next morning when Harry and I went out into the field, there was Alfred, ankle deep in water shovelling out clay from the bank.

813
01:41:02,440 --> 01:41:05,490
"What a big hole you've made," said I.

814
01:41:05,490 --> 01:41:09,000
"I believe I could get into it if I curled up very much."

815
01:41:09,000 --> 01:41:10,250
"Ah!"

816
01:41:10,250 --> 01:41:14,020
said my brother grimly, "you thought I couldn't do it."

817
01:41:14,020 --> 01:41:20,570
"Do you mean to say you aren't going to let us go shares," said Harry, reading his brother's tone instantly.

818
01:41:20,570 --> 01:41:30,330
"Not a share," said Alfred firmly, "this is going to be my cave, and if I find anyone in it without my leave, I'll throw him to the alligators."

819
01:41:30,330 --> 01:41:39,260
"There aren't any alligators," said Harry, "there are only ducks," and indeed, there were several swimming about the yellow waters of the pond.

820
01:41:39,260 --> 01:41:49,650
"All right," said Alfred cheerfully, sending a large spadeful of clay splashing into the pond, "I'll throw you to the ducks then, I daresay they'll do just as well."

821
01:41:49,650 --> 01:42:03,450
Alfred worked with what seemed to us superhuman vigour, and before evening there really was a hole in the clay bank big enough for him to get into, if, as I said, he curled himself up very much.

822
01:42:03,450 --> 01:42:12,070
"He'll be tired of it to-morrow," said Harry to me privately, reasoning from his former experience of his brother, "and then he'll let us have it."

823
01:42:12,070 --> 01:42:18,080
But the next day we found that the roof of the cave had fallen in.

824
01:42:18,080 --> 01:42:23,540
"No one need want to have it now," I said, but I was mistaken.

825
01:42:23,540 --> 01:42:34,790
The landslip, while filling up, had enlarged the hole, so that when the loose clay was cleared out, there was a space large enough for us all to have got in, even with the dogs.

826
01:42:34,790 --> 01:42:40,530
Alfred twisted some straw into a rope and made it, with string, into a rough mat.

827
01:42:40,530 --> 01:42:43,670
This be put at the bottom of his rough cave.

828
01:42:43,670 --> 01:42:49,030
I timidly offered to help with this, but my offers were sternly rejected.

829
01:42:49,030 --> 01:42:54,050
"You said I couldn't do it," he said, "and I'll jolly well show you I can."

830
01:42:54,050 --> 01:42:58,310
Harry came to me a little later when I was feeding my rabbits.

831
01:42:58,310 --> 01:43:11,550
"He's got it all so nice," he said, "he's roofed it over with a hurdle and he's put a bit of old tarpaulin over it, and he's fastening it down with big stones like the people in the Swiss Family Robinson; I wish he'd let us share in it."

832
01:43:11,550 --> 01:43:19,270
"Look here," I said, "let's walk into town and get him a present, then he'll see we're sorry we said he couldn't do it."

833
01:43:19,270 --> 01:43:30,700
In the broiling sun we walked the five miles into the town and back, returning with a large green sugarstick wrapped in coloured paper which had taken all our half-pence to buy.

834
01:43:30,700 --> 01:43:33,500
With this we approached the pond.

835
01:43:33,500 --> 01:43:39,970
Alfred was sitting in his cave with the raft moored at his feet; I waved the sugarstick in the air.

836
01:43:39,970 --> 01:43:48,560
"Look here, Alfred," I said "here's a sucre de pomme for you; we've been all the way to Dinan to get it, and we're sorry we said you couldn't."

837
01:43:48,560 --> 01:43:55,100
"You little duffers," he cried, "I don't want your sucre de pomme, I only wanted you to say you were sorry.

838
01:43:55,100 --> 01:43:58,490
You needn't have walked five miles in the broiling sun to do that.

839
01:43:58,490 --> 01:44:00,210
You'd like to come over, wouldn't you?"

840
01:44:00,210 --> 01:44:02,760
he added, unmooring the raft.

841
01:44:02,760 --> 01:44:07,460
"We really didn't mean to vex you," I said, as he came across.

842
01:44:07,460 --> 01:44:11,900
"Not another word," he said handsomely, and rowed us to the cave.

843
01:44:11,900 --> 01:44:28,000
It was a very soft cave, and we had no means of breaking the sucre de pomme, so we took it in turns to suck it; Alfred after some persuasion, consenting to join us in the feast, so as not to hurt our feelings, he said.

844
01:44:28,000 --> 01:44:40,400
That cave was a joy to us for many a day, though there was generally at least half an inch of water in it; and we didn't abandon it till the autumn rains had swelled the pond water, and raised it above the level of our cave.

845
01:44:40,400 --> 01:44:52,270
It was a grand day for us when we first discovered our stream; it was three or four fields from our house, and ran through a beautiful meadow with sloping woods on each side.

846
01:44:52,270 --> 01:44:58,010
Its bottom was partly of shining sand and stone, and in some places of clay.

847
01:44:58,010 --> 01:45:11,430
We built dams and bridges with the clay, we caught fish with butterfly nets in the sandy shallows; we called it the Nile and pretended that there were crocodiles in it, and that the rocks among the woods were temples and pyramids.

848
01:45:11,430 --> 01:45:16,160
One day Alfred proposed that we should try and find the source of it.

849
01:45:16,160 --> 01:45:35,700
"We shall have to travel through a very wild country," he said, "explorers always do and we shall want a good lot of provisions, for I don't suppose we shall get back before dinner-time, so you kids had better sneak as much bread-and-butter as you can at breakfast, and I'll sneak what I can out of the larder, and we'll start directly after breakfast to-morrow."

850
01:45:36,900 --> 01:45:49,720
We secured a goodly stock of provisions in an old nose-bag which we found in the stables, but it was so heavy that we were glad to hide it under the second hedge that we passed and go on with only what we could carry in our pockets.

851
01:45:49,720 --> 01:45:53,050
We struck the river at the usual point.

852
01:45:53,050 --> 01:46:02,070
"I think we ought to wade up," said Alfred, "there are no crocodiles in this part of the river, but the lions and tigers on the banks are something awful."

853
01:46:02,070 --> 01:46:07,440
So we waded up stream, which is tiring work, let me tell you.

854
01:46:07,440 --> 01:46:14,540
"I don't see a single lion," I said presently, "but I'm sure I saw a crocodile just now under that bank."

855
01:46:14,540 --> 01:46:20,960
So we got out and walked by the stream's edge on the short, fine, sun-warmed turf.

856
01:46:20,960 --> 01:46:29,900
But presently we came to the end of the field; the stream ran through a wood, and we had to take to wading again, but the water was much shallower and it was easy.

857
01:46:29,900 --> 01:46:35,980
We ate some of our provisions, sitting upon a large, flat, moss-covered stone, in the middle of the stream.

858
01:46:35,980 --> 01:46:38,080
Then we went on again.

859
01:46:38,080 --> 01:46:40,900
Harry began to get rather tired.

860
01:46:40,900 --> 01:46:44,320
"We shall never find the source of the stream," he said.

861
01:46:44,320 --> 01:46:49,000
"I shouldn't wonder if it's thousands of miles away, somewhere up by Paris I daresay.

862
01:46:49,000 --> 01:46:50,870
I vote we turn back."

863
01:46:50,870 --> 01:46:56,510
But his suggestion was howled down by the exploring party, and we went on.

864
01:46:56,510 --> 01:47:11,300
Through a meadow where the flax was drying in stocks, then through another wood we followed the stream, and then with a thrill of delight, we saw that the water ran from a little brick tunnel, the mouth of which was draped in a green veil of maiden-hair.

865
01:47:11,300 --> 01:47:14,260
I suppose it was about four feet high.

866
01:47:14,260 --> 01:47:18,490
"You'll turn back now," said Harry triumphantly.

867
01:47:18,490 --> 01:47:23,960
For all answer, Alfred stooped and plunged into the darkness of the little tunnel.

868
01:47:23,960 --> 01:47:26,450
I followed, and Harry brought up the rear.

869
01:47:26,450 --> 01:47:31,160
It was back-breaking work, but the floor was smooth.

870
01:47:31,160 --> 01:47:39,140
If we had had to pick our way, we could never have done it, for Alfred had only a few matches, and lighted one very occasionally.

871
01:47:39,140 --> 01:47:51,670
At last we found ourselves again in the dazzling sunlight, and behold our stream was meandering through a wonderful swamp full of grasses and curious flowers, whose like I have never seen elsewhere.

872
01:47:51,670 --> 01:48:01,460
Our stream got narrower and narrower, but we followed it faithfully, and at last, crashing through a hedge, found ourselves in a roadway.

873
01:48:01,460 --> 01:48:07,880
Opposite us in the high bank was a little stone basin into which water trickled from above.

874
01:48:07,880 --> 01:48:15,870
From this basin a narrow stream of water, not more than a foot wide, ran across the road and under the hedge.

875
01:48:15,870 --> 01:48:23,680
This was the source of our stream—this, a wayside well we had passed a thousand times!

876
01:48:23,680 --> 01:48:29,820
We finished our provisions, and knowing now where we were, went home by road.

877
01:48:29,820 --> 01:48:42,900
The swamp had coated us with black mud almost from head to foot, and in this condition we marched gaily into the garden where my mother was entertaining a company of rather smart friends at afternoon tea.

878
01:48:42,900 --> 01:48:46,120
The sequel was bed.

879
01:48:48,000 --> 01:48:49,900
End of Part 10

880
