882
01:49:02,100 --> 01:49:04,440
PART 11

883
01:49:05,980 --> 01:49:10,460
The happy memories of that golden time crowd thickly upon me.

884
01:49:10,460 --> 01:49:22,190
I see again the dewy freshness as of an enchanted world, that greeted us when we stole down, carrying our shoes in our hands long before the rest of the household was astir.

885
01:49:22,190 --> 01:50:02,580
I smell the scents of dead leaves and wood smoke, and it brings back to me the bonfires on autumn evenings when we used to play at Red Indians and sit round the fire telling stories, and when that palled, dig out from the grey and red ashes the potatoes we had put there to roast, and eat the halfcooked, blackened, smoke-flavoured dainties with keenest appreciation; the rare days when we went to Dinard and paddled in the shallow waters of the bay between blue sky and gold sand, picking limpets from the rocks and wishing for wooden spades, which Dinard then, at least, did not produce.

886
01:50:03,780 --> 01:50:15,780
A part of the infinite charm of those days lies in the fact that we were never bored, and children are bored much more often and much more deeply than their elders suppose.

887
01:50:15,780 --> 01:50:23,490
I remember an occasion when some well-meaning friends persuaded my mother that my education was being neglected.

888
01:50:23,490 --> 01:50:33,940
I was sent to a select French school, Mademoiselle Fauchet's in Divan, but owing to some misunderstanding I arrived five days before the other girls.

889
01:50:33,940 --> 01:50:40,750
Mademoiselle Fauchet kindly consented to overlook the mistake and keep me till the other girls arrived.

890
01:50:40,750 --> 01:50:50,630
I had a paintbox which pleased me for the first day, but the boredom of the other four days is branded on my memory in grey letters.

891
01:50:50,630 --> 01:50:55,630
Mademoiselle Fauchet was busy in visiting her friends and receiving them.

892
01:50:55,630 --> 01:50:59,020
She took me out for a serious walk every day.

893
01:50:59,020 --> 01:51:07,080
We walked for an hour, and then Mademoiselle Fauchet returned to her visiting and I to the bare schoolroom.

894
01:51:07,080 --> 01:51:12,520
I had brought few books with me and these I devoured in an hour or two.

895
01:51:12,520 --> 01:51:18,940
There were no books in the schoolroom but lesson-books, thumbed, dog's eared and ink-stained.

896
01:51:18,940 --> 01:51:26,470
There was no one to talk to save the severe cook, who was kind to me in her way but didn't understand children.

897
01:51:26,470 --> 01:51:36,640
There was a grey-walled garden full of fruit that I must not touch and a locked book-case in Mademoiselle Fauchet's salon, full of books that I must not read.

898
01:51:36,640 --> 01:51:43,160
I was not conscious of being unhappy, only bored, bored to extinction.

899
01:51:43,160 --> 01:51:49,870
On the fourth day I persuaded Mademoiselle Faucher to vary our prim walk round the town.

900
01:51:49,870 --> 01:51:54,280
She asked me where I would like to go, and I said La Fontaine.

901
01:51:54,280 --> 01:52:07,370
Mademoiselle Fauchet meant to be kind according to her lights, but she was the ideal schoolmistress, grey-haired, prim, bloodless; however she conceded this to me and I was grateful.

902
01:52:07,370 --> 01:52:10,060
We started for La Fontaine.

903
01:52:11,440 --> 01:52:17,570
La Fontaine is one of the show places of Divan, as it has a natural fountain of mineral water.

904
01:52:17,570 --> 01:52:26,520
There is a casino where balls and fêtes and merry-makings are held, where bands play and little coloured lamps glimmer in the trees.

905
01:52:26,520 --> 01:52:44,700
All this awakened no associations, stirred nothing in me, for I had never been to a fête at La Fontaine, but below the platform on which the casino was built, ran a stream, our stream, our Nile, on its way to join the river.

906
01:52:44,700 --> 01:52:47,820
The sight of it was too much for me.

907
01:52:47,820 --> 01:53:05,450
I remembered our happy exploring parties the muddy dams we had built across it; I thought of the rabbits and the garden at home, and my brothers and my mother, and in the midst of one of mademoiselle's platitudes on the beauty of the scene, I began to run.

908
01:53:05,450 --> 01:53:14,600
Mademoiselle Fauchet called after me, she even ran a little, I believe, but the legs of fifty are not a match for the legs of ten.

909
01:53:14,600 --> 01:53:18,930
I ran faster and faster down the avenue of chestnuts.

910
01:53:18,930 --> 01:53:24,940
I reached our meadow where our stream ran just the same as in the days when I was free to make a paradise of it.

911
01:53:24,940 --> 01:53:36,610
I ran on and on, up the slope over the cornfield, across the road, through our own meadow, and never stopped till I flung myself into my sister's arms.

912
01:53:36,610 --> 01:53:44,680
Then, and not till then, the fact dawned upon me that I had run away from school.

913
01:53:46,040 --> 01:53:49,520
I don't recall the explanations that must have followed on my return.

914
01:53:49,520 --> 01:53:54,360
I know that I cried a great deal, and felt that I had committed an awful crime.

915
01:53:54,360 --> 01:54:05,910
I couldn't explain my feelings to myself, but I knew that in the same circumstances I should have done the same again, though I wept heartfelt tears of penitence for having done it at all.

916
01:54:05,910 --> 01:54:12,300
I think my mother must have understood something of what I went through, for she did not send me back.

917
01:54:13,960 --> 01:54:21,480
Another period of acute boredom came to me some years later when I went to stay with some friends of my mother's in the north of London.

918
01:54:21,480 --> 01:54:32,930
They lived in a dreary square apart from the main thoroughfare, so that if you looked out over the brown wire blinds you never saw anything pass but butchers' and bakers' carts.

919
01:54:32,930 --> 01:54:45,430
If I went for a walk, the sordid ugliness of Islington outraged the feelings of a child who had always found her greatest pleasures and life's greatest beauties in the green country.

920
01:54:45,430 --> 01:54:58,280
The people with whom I was staying were the kindest-hearted people in the world; they would have done anything to please me if they had only known what I wanted, but they didn't know, that was just it.

921
01:54:59,280 --> 01:55:05,800
The dining-room was mahogany and leather with two books in it, the Bible and Family Prayers.

922
01:55:05,800 --> 01:55:16,680
They stood on the side-board, flanked on one side by a terra-cotta water-bottle oozing sad tears all day into a terracotta saucer, and on the other by a tea-caddy.

923
01:55:16,680 --> 01:55:29,100
Upstairs in the drawing-room, which was only used on Sundays, were a few illustrated giftbooks, albums, and types of beauty arranged on a polished, oval, walnut centre table.

924
01:55:29,100 --> 01:55:31,910
The piano was kept locked.

925
01:55:31,910 --> 01:55:38,460
There were a few old bound volumes of Good Words, which I had read again and again.

926
01:55:38,460 --> 01:55:48,820
The master of the house, a doctor, was, my mother tells me, a man of brains, but I only saw him at meals and then he seldom spoke.

927
01:55:48,820 --> 01:55:56,850
The lady of the house had a heart full of kindness, and a mind full of court circular, she talked of nothing else.

928
01:55:56,850 --> 01:56:03,370
Her daughters were kind to me in their way, and the games I had with them were my only relaxation.

929
01:56:03,370 --> 01:56:09,420
The doctor talked very occasionally of his patients, and this interested me.

930
01:56:09,420 --> 01:56:18,930
One night I went into the surgery and found the bottles of medicine which his assistant had made up, standing in a row waiting for their white paper wrappers.

931
01:56:18,930 --> 01:56:31,580
I didn't in the least realise what I was doing when I thought to escape from my boredom by mixing the contents of these bottles in a large jug, and then in partially filling up the bottles again with the mixture.

932
01:56:31,580 --> 01:56:52,660
When I had filled and corked them all, I slipped away; it was done in pure mischief with no thought of consequences; but when I woke that night in bed and suddenly remembered that I had heard that medicines that were given for some complaints were bad for others, and absolutely harmful, my heart stood still.

933
01:56:52,660 --> 01:57:00,930
Suppose some poor sick person died, whom Dr.—— would have cured, because I had mixed his medicine with something else.

934
01:57:00,930 --> 01:57:16,560
I fully resolved to own up the next morning, but the next morning I reflected that perhaps some of the people that had taken my mixture might die of it and then I should be hanged for murder; 'it seemed to me wiser to wait and see what happened.

935
01:57:17,880 --> 01:57:37,980
If any one did die, and Dr. ——— were accused of poisoning his patients, I would come forward in the court of justice, as people did in the books, and own that I, and I alone, had been to blame, malting my confession among the sympathetic tears of usher and jury, the judge himself not remaining dry-eyed.

936
01:57:39,040 --> 01:57:46,590
This scene so much appealed to me that I almost forgot that before it could be enacted somebody would have to die of my mixture.

937
01:57:46,590 --> 01:57:55,400
When I remembered this I wept in secret; when I thought of the scene in which I should nobly own my guilt, I secretly exulted.

938
01:57:55,400 --> 01:57:57,800
I was not bored now.

939
01:57:57,800 --> 01:58:03,570
Whatever else might be the effect of my mixtures, they had certainly cured my boredom.

940
01:58:03,570 --> 01:58:33,670
Day after day passed by in spasms of alternate remorse and day-dreaming; every day I expected Dr. ——— to announce at dinner that some of his patients had breathed their last in inexplicable circumstances, but he never said anything of the kind, and when a week had passed, I was convinced that so good a doctor never gave anybody any medicine that could do them any harm in any condition, and that one of his medicines was as good for any complaint as any others.

941
01:58:33,670 --> 01:58:48,930
Whether this was so, or whether someone had been a witness of my act in the surgery, and had re-made the mixtures, I shall never know, but in the reaction following my anxiety, boredom settled down upon me more heavily than ever.

942
01:58:48,930 --> 01:58:56,470
I wrote a frantic letter to my mother begging her to take me away, for I was so miserable, I wished I was dead.

943
01:58:56,470 --> 01:59:02,000
Not having any stamps, I gave this letter to Mrs. ——— to post.

944
01:59:02,000 --> 01:59:09,500
I don't suppose she thought she was doing any harm when she opened and read it, and I hope she was gratified by its contents.

945
01:59:09,500 --> 01:59:15,970
She added a note to my mother begging her to accede to my request, and to take me away at once.

946
01:59:15,970 --> 01:59:24,660
It was years before I forgave her for reading that letter, and to this day I am afraid she has never forgiven me for writing it.

947
01:59:25,700 --> 01:59:35,280
My mother was at Penshurst at the time; I was sent down to her in deep disgrace, and my mother received me with gentle reproaches that cut me to the heart.

948
01:59:35,280 --> 01:59:45,220
My sister was exceedingly angry with me, perhaps with some cause, and pointed out to me how ungrateful it was to repay Mrs. ——— by writing such a letter.

949
01:59:45,220 --> 01:59:47,830
I defended myself stoutly.

950
01:59:47,830 --> 02:00:02,320
"I wrote it for mamma and not for her," and though I was sorry for having hurt the feelings of one I knew had tried to be kind to me, yet I fear the verdict of my unregenerate heart was, "serve her right."

951
02:00:02,320 --> 02:00:18,320
I felt that I was being unjustly blamed, and though I was sorry I would not say so, and the next morning I wandered up through Penshurst churchyard, and through a little wicket-gate into the park, where the splendour of a blaze of buttercups, burst upon me.

952
02:00:18,320 --> 02:00:26,820
The may-trees were silver-white, the skylarks singing overhead; I sat down under a white may-tree.

953
02:00:26,820 --> 02:00:38,780
The spirit of the spring breathed softly round me, and when I got up to go back I was in love and charity with all men and all women except Mrs. ———.

954
02:00:38,780 --> 02:00:55,610
"I am sorry if I have been naughty," I said to my sister; "I didn't mean to be, but—" "That will do," she said, skilfully stopping my confidences; "now I do hope you are going to try and be a good girl, and not make dear mamma unhappy."

955
02:00:55,610 --> 02:00:59,060
"I will be good," I said; "oh, I will indeed!"

956
02:00:59,060 --> 02:01:08,040
And as long as I stayed among the golden buttercups and silver may-bushes, I believe I was moderately good.

957
02:01:09,320 --> 02:01:11,300
End of Part 11

