960
02:01:23,700 --> 02:01:26,080
PART 12

961
02:01:27,720 --> 02:01:36,960
When I began to write of the recollections of my childhood, I thought that all of those days which I remember could well be told in these twelve chapters.

962
02:01:36,960 --> 02:01:47,210
But the remembrances of that long ago time crowded thickly on me, and I wandered in the pleasant fields of memory, where time ceases to be.

963
02:01:47,210 --> 02:01:58,120
So my twelfth chapter is reached, and finds me still only ten years old, and finds me, moreover, with not one-tenth of the events of those ten years recorded.

964
02:01:58,120 --> 02:02:04,640
If only one's memory were as good for the events of yesterday—of last week, of last year!

965
02:02:04,640 --> 02:02:18,600
I have left myself no space to tell you of my adventures in Germany and France during the war of 1870, of my English school-days, of much that is not ever to be forgotten by me.

966
02:02:18,600 --> 02:02:27,270
Since I must needs choose one out of many remembrances, I choose my Kentish home, dearer to me than all.

967
02:02:27,270 --> 02:02:37,880
After many wanderings my mother took a house at Halstead, "The Hall" it was called but the house itself did not lend itself to the pretensions of its name.

968
02:02:37,880 --> 02:02:49,970
A long, low, red-brick house, that might have been common-place but for the roses and ivy that clung to the front of it, and the rich, heavy jasmine that covered the side.

969
02:02:49,970 --> 02:03:01,970
There was a smooth lawn with chestnut-trees round it and a big garden, where flowers and fruit and vegetables grew together, as they should, without jealousy or class-distinction.

970
02:03:01,970 --> 02:03:10,920
There never were such peonies as grew among our currant-bushes, nor such apricots as hung among the leaves on the sunny south wall.

971
02:03:10,920 --> 02:03:24,050
From a laburnum-tree in a corner of the lawn we children slung an improvised hammock, and there I used to read and dream, and watch the swaying green gold of leaf and blossom.

972
02:03:24,050 --> 02:03:27,990
Our garden ran round three sides of a big pond.

973
02:03:27,990 --> 02:03:32,230
Perhaps it was true that the pond did not make the house more healthy.

974
02:03:32,230 --> 02:03:35,140
It certainly madeit more interesting.

975
02:03:35,140 --> 02:03:55,870
Besides the raft (which was but a dull thing when the boys were away at school), there were nooks among the laburnums and lilacs that grew thickly round the pond, nooks where one could hide with one's favourite books, and be secure from the insistent and irritating demands so often made on one's time by one's elders.

976
02:03:55,870 --> 02:04:01,910
For grown-up people never thought of spoiling their clothes by penetrating the shrubbery.

977
02:04:01,910 --> 02:04:15,300
Here, on many a sunny day, have I lounged away the morning, stifling conscience with Mrs. Ewing's tales, and refusing to remember the tangle of untidiness in which I had left my room involved.

978
02:04:15,300 --> 02:04:32,680
For I had a little room of my own, a little, little room, with a long low window and a window-ledge, where bright plants in pots, encouraged by the western sun, withstood the intermittence of my attentions, and blossomed profusely.

979
02:04:33,760 --> 02:04:42,730
My bookcase stood by this window, an old mahogany bookcase with a deep top drawer, that let down to form a writing-table.

980
02:04:42,730 --> 02:04:55,470
Here I used to sit and write—verse, verse, always verse—and dream of the days when I should be a great poet, like Shakespeare, or Christina Rossetti!

981
02:04:55,470 --> 02:04:56,920
Ah me!

982
02:04:56,920 --> 02:04:58,970
that day is long in coming!

983
02:04:58,970 --> 02:05:02,010
But I never doubted then that it would come.

984
02:05:02,010 --> 02:05:10,530
Here I wrote and dreamed, and never showed my verses or told my dreams for many a long month.

985
02:05:10,530 --> 02:05:15,370
But when I was fifteen I ventured to show some verses to my mother.

986
02:05:15,370 --> 02:05:31,000
She showed them to Mr. Japp then editor of Good Words and the Sunday Magazine and never shall I forget the rapture of delight and of gratitude with which I received the news that my verses had been accepted.

987
02:05:31,000 --> 02:05:38,130
By-and-by they were printed; and I got a cheque for a guinea—a whole guinea, think of it!

988
02:05:38,130 --> 02:05:42,170
Now the day when I should be a poet seemed almost at hand.

989
02:05:42,170 --> 02:05:45,070
Had I not had a poem printed ?

990
02:05:45,070 --> 02:06:04,910
Besides the desk and the well-oiled key, that formed so excellent a defence against "the boys"—for what young poet could ever set down a line with the possibility of even the best-loved brothers looking over her shoulder?—my little room had another feature, by turns a terror and a charm.

991
02:06:04,910 --> 02:06:23,800
A little trapdoor in the ceiling led to that mysterious and delightful region between the roof and the beams, a dark passage leading all round the house, and leading to—oh, deep and abiding joy!—to a little door that opened on the roof itself.

992
02:06:23,800 --> 02:06:30,840
This, until the higher powers discovered it, was a safer haven even than the shrubbery.

993
02:06:30,840 --> 02:06:44,230
Enclosed by four pointed roofs of tiles was a central space – safe, secluded—whence one could see the world around, oneself invisible, or at least unseen.

994
02:06:44,230 --> 02:06:52,710
Another trap-door, from the linen-closet by the boys' bedroom, afforded them an equal access to this same paradise.

995
02:06:52,710 --> 02:06:59,860
We kept a store of books and good things in the hollow of the roof, and many a pleasant picnic have we enjoyed there.

996
02:06:59,860 --> 02:07:09,000
Happy, vanished days, when to be on the roof and to eat tinned pineapple in secret constituted happiness!

997
02:07:09,000 --> 02:07:14,800
It was an uneventful, peaceful, pleasant time.

998
02:07:14,800 --> 02:07:26,040
The only really exciting thing was the presence, within a stone's throw of our house, of our landlady's son, who lived all alone in a little cottage standing in the fields.

999
02:07:26,040 --> 02:07:35,260
He was reported mad by the world, eccentric by his friends; but, as we found him, perfectly harmless.

1000
02:07:35,260 --> 02:07:53,710
His one delusion, as far as I know, was that he was the rightful owner, nay, more, the rightful tenant of our house, and about once in six months he used to terrify the whole household by appearing with a carpet bag at the front door and announcing that he had come to take possession.

1001
02:07:53,710 --> 02:08:05,230
This used to alarm us all very much, because if a gentleman is eccentric enough to wish to "take possession" of another person's house there is no knowing what he may be eccentric enough to do next.

1002
02:08:05,230 --> 02:08:11,410
But he was always persuaded to go away peaceably, and I don't think we need have been so frightened.

1003
02:08:11,410 --> 02:08:27,390
Once while he was in the drawing-room being persuaded by my mother, I peeped into the carpet bag he had left in the hall: It contained three empty bottles that had held mixed pickles, a loaf of bread and a barrister's wig and gown.

1004
02:08:27,390 --> 02:08:31,950
Poor gentleman, I am afraid he was very eccentric indeed.

1005
02:08:31,950 --> 02:08:35,720
Did I say that his existence was our only excitement.

1006
02:08:35,720 --> 02:08:42,280
Is it possible that I have forgotten the dreadful day when my brother Alfred shot a fox?

1007
02:08:42,280 --> 02:08:46,780
He drew me mysteriously aside one morning after breakfast.

1008
02:08:46,780 --> 02:08:50,510
"Daisy," he said, "can you keep a secret?"

1009
02:08:50,510 --> 02:08:53,450
I could, I asseverated.

1010
02:08:53,450 --> 02:09:01,370
He drew me into his room, locked the door, and then opening a cupboard displayed the body of a big dog-fox.

1011
02:09:01,370 --> 02:09:03,300
"Where did you get it?"

1012
02:09:03,300 --> 02:09:04,680
"I shot it."

1013
02:09:04,680 --> 02:09:06,490
"Oh, poor thing."

1014
02:09:06,490 --> 02:09:10,440
"Poor thing indeed," repeated my, brother indignantly.

1015
02:09:10,440 --> 02:09:15,270
"Don't you know no one would ever speak to me again if they knew I had shot a fox?"

1016
02:09:15,270 --> 02:09:17,320
"Then why did you?"

1017
02:09:17,320 --> 02:09:19,530
was the natural rejoinder.

1018
02:09:19,530 --> 02:09:21,400
"I didn't mean to.

1019
02:09:21,400 --> 02:09:25,830
I was out this morning after wood pigeons, and I saw something move in the bushes.

1020
02:09:25,830 --> 02:09:29,640
I thought it was a rabbit and I fired, and it was this.

1021
02:09:29,640 --> 02:09:31,890
What shall I do with it?"

1022
02:09:31,890 --> 02:09:36,190
"Bury it, we can have a splendid funeral," I said.

1023
02:09:36,190 --> 02:09:38,020
"You baby!"

1024
02:09:38,020 --> 02:09:46,900
I was constantly forgetting that Alfred, at seventeen, was grown-up, and that our old games no longer interested him.

1025
02:09:46,900 --> 02:09:49,460
"Well stuff it, then."

1026
02:09:50,480 --> 02:09:55,080
You will hardly believe it, but we really did try to stuff that fox.

1027
02:09:55,080 --> 02:09:59,610
My brother skinned it, skilfully enough, and we buried the body.

1028
02:09:59,610 --> 02:10:02,720
We bought a shilling book on taxidermy.

1029
02:10:02,720 --> 02:10:10,750
We spent many shillings on chemicals; we nailed the fox's skin to the inside of the cupboard door and operated on it.

1030
02:10:10,750 --> 02:10:32,680
My interest in the process was not lessened by the fact that I felt that the fox when stuffed must be kept from all eyes but our own, hidden for ever in the depths of that cupboard, lest the world in general should find out that Alfred had shot a fox and that I had been an accessory after the fact, and should so decline "ever to speak to us again."

1031
02:10:33,820 --> 02:10:35,300
But we never stuffed it.

1032
02:10:35,300 --> 02:10:49,040
We never even succeeded in curing the skin, which after awhile cried aloud for vengeance so unmistakably that we had to take it out and bury it secretly beside the body it had covered.

1033
02:10:50,480 --> 02:11:01,430
Both interments were conducted in the very early morning before even the maids were stirring, when the dew was grey on the grass, and the scent of the wet earth was sweet and fresh.

1034
02:11:01,430 --> 02:11:05,380
When all the fox was buried I breathed more freely.

1035
02:11:05,380 --> 02:11:10,650
Perhaps no one would ever know, and people would go on "speaking to" us.

1036
02:11:10,650 --> 02:11:21,160
I remember after the burial of the skin we went for a walks through the long wet grass, and came home with wet feet and happy hearts.

1037
02:11:22,880 --> 02:11:28,850
Oh, those dewy mornings—the resurrection of light and life in the woods and fields!

1038
02:11:28,850 --> 02:11:39,870
Would that it were possible for all children to live in the country where they may' drink in, consciously or unconsciously, the dear delights of green meadow and dappled woodland!

1039
02:11:39,870 --> 02:12:11,220
The delight in green things growing, in the tender beauty of the evening light on grey pastures, the glorious splendour of the noonday sun on meadows golden with buttercups, the browns and purples of winter woodlands—this is a delight that grows with one's growth—a delight that "age cannot wither nor custom stale," a delight that the years who take from us so much can never take away—can but intensify and make more keen and precious.

1040
02:12:12,220 --> 02:12:13,690
"Nature never did betray

1041
02:12:13,690 --> 02:12:16,260
The heart that loved her."

1042
02:12:18,080 --> 02:12:33,860
My book of memory lies open always at the page where are the pictures of Kentish cherry orchards, field and farm and gold-dim woodlands starred with primroses, light copses where the blue-bells and wind-flowers grow.

1043
02:12:33,860 --> 02:12:39,090
Yes, blue-bells and wind-flowers to me and to all who love them.

1044
02:12:39,090 --> 02:12:46,050
Botanists who pull the poor, pretty things to pieces may call them hyacinths and anemones.

1045
02:12:46,050 --> 02:12:53,680
And most plainly of all, among the dream pictures shows our old garden at home.

1046
02:12:56,080 --> 02:12:58,900
There is a grey-walled garden far away

1047
02:12:58,900 --> 02:13:02,590
From noise and smoke of cities where the hours

1048
02:13:02,590 --> 02:13:06,190
Pass with soft wings among the happy flowers

1049
02:13:06,190 --> 02:13:09,690
And lovely leisure blossoms every day.

1050
02:13:09,690 --> 02:13:14,360
There, tall and white, the sceptral lily blows;

1051
02:13:14,360 --> 02:13:17,270
There grow the pansy pink and columbine,

1052
02:13:17,270 --> 02:13:20,300
Brave holly-hocks and star-white jessamine

1053
02:13:20,300 --> 02:13:23,530
And the red glory of the royal rose.

1054
02:13:23,530 --> 02:13:27,640
There greeny glow-worms gem the dusky lawn

1055
02:13:27,640 --> 02:13:31,300
The lime-trees breathe their fragrance to the night,

1056
02:13:31,300 --> 02:13:35,120
Pink roses sleep, and dream that they are white

1057
02:13:35,120 --> 02:13:38,530
Until they wake to colour with the dawn.

1058
02:13:38,530 --> 02:13:41,860
There in the splendour of the sultry noon

1059
02:13:41,860 --> 02:13:44,810
The sunshine sleeps upon the garden bed,

1060
02:13:44,810 --> 02:13:48,090
Where the white poppy droops a drowsy head

1061
02:13:48,090 --> 02:13:51,800
And dreams of kisses from the white full moon.

1062
02:13:51,800 --> 02:13:56,090
And there, all day, my heart goes wandering,

1063
02:13:56,090 --> 02:13:59,580
Because there first my heart began to know

1064
02:13:59,580 --> 02:14:02,670
The glories of the summer and the snow,

1065
02:14:02,670 --> 02:14:06,140
The loveliness of harvest and of spring.

1066
02:14:06,140 --> 02:14:09,820
There may be fairer gardens—but I know

1067
02:14:09,820 --> 02:14:12,490
There is no other garden half so dear,

1068
02:14:12,490 --> 02:14:16,720
Because 'tis there, this many, many a year,

1069
02:14:16,720 --> 02:14:21,360
The sacred sweet white flowers of memory grow.

1070
